<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0003 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-05 19:38 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Barak Says Israel Will Not Tolerate Terrorism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak ordered a swift investigation into two ill-fated car
bombings in northern Israel Sunday afternoon, saying that Israel
would not tolerate any terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"A major incident has been averted with the perpetrators
possibly killed...The Israeli government will not tolerate any
terror act against its citizens," Barak's office said in a
statement in response to the two car bombings.
</P>
<P>
Two occupants in a car were killed and two passers-by wounded
in the first explosion in Tiberias, near the Sea of
Galilee. Minutes later, a second car bombing rocked the port city
of Haifa, killing one inside the car.
</P>
<P>
Polices said the two car bombings were possibly "terror
attacks." They said the three dead were possibly terrorists on
their way to carry out attacks against Israelis.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy expressed "serious concern"
over the two incidents, urged the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) to take tough measures to curb terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Peace and blood can not exist," he told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
The bombings came hours after Barak and PNA Chairman Yasser
Arafat signed a deal in Egypt Saturday night to revive the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli cabinet ratified the deal by an overwhelming
majority Sunday afternoon, paving the way for the implementation
of the U.S.-brokered Wye accords, signed and then frozen by
Barak's hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The 23-member cabinet voted 21-2 to approve the agreement,
signed at the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh in the
presence of U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky from the Yisrael b'Aliya, or
Russian immigrant party, and Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy of the
Right wing National Religious Party, were the only two ministers
who voted against the deal.
</P>
<P>
The accord is the first agreement since Barak took office in
July promising to revive the peace process on all its tracks.
</P>
<P>
Barak said at the cabinet meeting that the major achievement
of the agreement was to have delayed the transfer of some land
from joint control to full Palestinian control by three months.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Israel would complete the troop
withdrawals stipulated by the Wye agreement by January 2000,
rather than by mid-November under the original Wye timeline.
</P>
<P>
Under the new deal, Israel and the Palestinians are supposed
to have entered an advance stage of permanent talks by early
2000, which would help reduce the potential risk of confrontation
between the two sides raised by the troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have set February 2000 as the target date for a
framework for the permanent talks, which deal with thorny issues
like the Palestinian statehood and Jerusalem, and September 2000
for an over-all deal aiming to end century-old conflict.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militant groups Hamas and Jihad have threatened to
stage attacks against Israel to derail the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two militant groups, which oppose the Israeli-Palestinian
peacemaking, have carried out a series of suicide bombings
killing scores of Israelis since the signing of the historic Oslo
accords in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In less than two weeks after the Wye accords were signed in
last October, the two groups staged two failed attacks against
Israelis, one outside a bloc of Jewish settlements in Gaza and
one in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
In responding to the latest peace deal, Hamas spiritual leader
Sheik Ahmed Yassin said his supporters reserved the right to
resist Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
Barak's statement said the Israeli government would decide how
to react after the investigation ends, implying that the peace
process would not be halted by the incidents. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
