<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Calls For International Control in E.Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Britain on Sunday called on the
Indonesian government to allow the international community to help
restore order in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on reports that more than 100 people may have been
killed in East Timor in the violence by pro-Indonesia militias
following last week's independence vote, Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said he was alarmed by the deteriorating situation in that
territory.
</P>
<P>
"If the government of Indonesia cannot get its own security
forces to restore order, it should allow the international
community to assist in securing an orderly transition to
independence in East Timor," the foreign secretary said.
</P>
<P>
He said he would use a trip to Japan on Monday to discuss the
crisis with Japanese Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura and would
also contact other regional powers while he was in Asia.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Cook told BBC television from Finland, where he was
attending a meeting of European Union foreign ministers, that EU
ministers had agreed on a number of steps to ensure the Indonesian
government to ensure security in the territory.
</P>
<P>
"We are getting the right words on that out of Jakarta. As yet
we have not seen the right action on East Timor," he said, adding
that he hoped top Indonesian officials would ensure orders from
Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
The United Nations announced on Saturday that 78.5 percent of
East Timorese had rejected Jakarta's offer of broad autonomy,
putting the former Portuguese colony on the road to independence.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
