<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The following are economic
briefs from the Middle East.
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Minister of Higher Education and Scientific
Research of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) Sheikh Nahyan Bin
Mubarak Al Nahyan has announced the establishment of a national
institute for petroleum which will start functioning from
September 20, 2000.
</P>
<P>
Local press on Sunday quoted the minister as saying that the
institute will respond to the needs of the petroleum industry in
the UAE. The institute will also admit citizens of other Gulf and
Arab states.
</P>
<P>
RABAT -- Upon the implementation of the European Union-Moroccan
partnership agreement in early 2000, the economic survey center in
Casablanca anticipates that Morocco will consequently lose 30
percent of its custom revenues.
</P>
<P>
In its monthly report, the center estimates Morocco's losses at
about 6.8 billion dirhams (700 million U.S. dollars), on account
of the cut in custom fees on imported commodities and materials
from EU states which represent some 64 percent of the country's
overall foreign trade, it was reported by Sunday's Arab daily "Al
Hayat."
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- The Parsons International company of the United
States has won a contract for the expansion of the Abu Dhabi
international airport at a total cost of 600 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Parsons will undertake the coordination work with the project
consultants and supervise the construction works.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian Minister of Economy and Trade Mohammed
al-Imadi said the annual growth of the gross domestic product of
the country has reached 14.7 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Local press quoted Sunday the minister as saying that a just
and comprehensive peace is one of Syria's strategic targets,
emphasizing that Syria calls for true peace throughout the region,
an end to occupation, and a secure enviroment for all. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
