<HEADLINE> African Leaders Arrive in Tripoli for Summit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TRIPOLI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Seven African heads of state
have arrived in Tripoli, capital of Libya, so far Sunday to attend
the upcoming extraordinary summit meeting of the Organization of
African Unity (OAU) scheduled for Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Ghana President Jerry John Rawlings was the first head of state
to arrive at the Meatega Airport in Tripoli and greeted by Libyan
leader Muammar Ghaddafi.
</P>
<P>
The other presidents included Robert Mugabe of Zimbabwe, Bakili
Muluzi of Malawi, Malan Bacai Sanha of Guinea Bissau, Daouda Malam
Wanke of Niger.
</P>
<P>
Liberian Vice President Enoch Doglea and Algerian Foreign
Minister Ahmed Al Attaf, who was representing President Abdelaziz
Bouteflida, also arrived in Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
Other heads of state of the OAU member states are coming later
in the day.
</P>
<P>
During their stay, they will also attend the ongoing
celebrations for the 30th anniversary of the Libyan Revolution
which overthrew the monarchy on September 1, 1969.
</P>
<P>
The two-day summit meeting will review and possibly renew OAU
Charter which has not been revised since it was signed in Addis
Ababa on May 25, 1963. 
</P>
</TEXT>
