<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Two Car Bombs Rock Israel After Peace Deal Signed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 5 (Xinhua) -- At least three people were
killed in two separate car bombs suspected to be carried out by
terrorists in two northern Israeli towns Sunday, hours after
Israel and the Palestinians signed an agreement to revive the
stalled peace process.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Foreign Minister David Levy expressed "serious concern"
over the two incidents, urged the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) to take tough measures to curb terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"Peace and blood can not exist," he told Israel Radio.
</P>
<P>
Two people in an exploded car were killed and two passers-by
were wounded in the first explosion in the city of Tiberias, near
the Sea of Galilee. Minutes later, one person was killed in a
second car bombing in the northern port city of Haifa.
</P>
<P>
Polices said the two car bombings were apparently "terror
attacks." They said the two dead in the first explosion were
possibly terrorists on their way to carry out attacks against
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The bombings came hours after Israeli Prime Minister Ehud
Barak and PNA Chairman Yasser Arafat signed the revised version of
the Wye interim accord in Egypt.
</P>
<P>
Barak's cabinet ratified the deal by an overwhelming majority
Sunday afternoon, paving the way for the implementation of the
U.S.-brokered Wye accords, signed and then frozen by Barak's
hard-line predecessor Benjamin Netanyahu.
</P>
<P>
The 23-member cabinet voted 21-2 to approve the agreement,
signed at the Egyptian Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh in the
presence of United States Secretary of State Madeleine Albright in
the early hours of Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Interior Minister Natan Sharansky from the Yisrael b'Aliya, a
Russian immigrants party, and Housing Minister Yitzhak Levy of
the right-wing National Religious Party, were the only two
ministers who voted against the deal.
</P>
<P>
The accord is the first agreement to be signed since Barak took
office in July with the promise to revive the peace process on all
its tracks.
</P>
<P>
Barak said at the cabinet meeting that the major achievement of
the agreement was to have delayed the transfer of some land from
joint control to full Palestinian control by three months.
</P>
<P>
According to the agreement, Israel would complete the troop
withdrawals stipulated by the Wye agreement by January 2000,
rather than by mid-November under the original Wye timetable.
</P>
<P>
Under the new deal, Israel and the Palestinians are supposed to
have entered an advance stage of permanent talks by early 2000,
which would help reduce the potential risk of confrontation
between the two sides raised by the troop withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
The two sides have set February 2000 as the target date for a
framework for the permanent talks, which deal with thorny issues
like the Palestinian statehood and Jerusalem, and September 2000
for an overall deal aimed at ending the century-old conflict
between the two sides.
</P>
<P>
The Islamic militant groups Hamas and Jihad have threatened to
stage attacks against Israel to derail the peace process.
</P>
<P>
The two militant groups, which oppose the Israeli-Palestinian
peacemaking, have carried out a series of suicide bombings
killing scores of Israelis since the signing of the historic Oslo
accords in 1993.
</P>
<P>
In less than two weeks after the Wye accords were signed
last October, the two groups staged two failed attacks against
Israelis, one outside a bloc of Jewish settlements in Gaza and one
in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the latest peace deal, Hamas spiritual leader
Sheik Ahmed Yassin said his supporters reserved the right to
resist Israeli occupation.
</P>
<P>
In his speech at the signing ceremony in Sharm el-Sheikh,
Barak stressed the need to battle terrorism.
</P>
<P>
"We must prevent terrorism from derailing our peace efforts
and fight it with all our might. The battle for peace does not
tolerate threats of violence and any kind of act of terrorism," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat reiterated the PNA commitment to security at the
ceremony.
</P>
<P>
After Sunday's cabinet meeting, Barak's office issued a
statement saying that the latest peace agreement will enhance
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
"Prime Minister Barak said that he is convinced that the
political process will strengthen the long-term security of the
State of Israel and its citizens," the statement said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
