<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African Officer Selected for U.N. Mission in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations (U.N.)
has selected a South African military official as one of 90 U.N.
military liaison officers (MLOs) to advise on the implementation
of a peace-keeping operation in the Democratic Republic of the
Congo (DRC).
</P>
<P>
Puso Tladi, spokesman for the Defense Ministry, said that
Colonel Hans Swart would leave Monday for Kenyan capital Nairobi
where he would start a U.N. mission induction training course
Wednesday and then leave for Ugandan capital Kampala Saturday, the
day after the course ends.
</P>
<P>
So far, 30 military liaison officers have been appointed by the
U.N. They will be deployed in different areas to deal with the DRC
 conflict and will submit a report to U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan on the security situation on the ground, which will help
establish procedures for the deployment of a full-scale
peace-keeping operation.
</P>
<P>
Swart is one of the eight officers, whose name were submitted
to the U.N. by the South African government for possible selection
as military liaison officers.
</P>
<P>
It is not known whether any of the other officers may be
selected at a later stage.
</P>
<P>
"Many people confuse these MLOs with observers," Tladi said,
adding that the MLOs will only come in at a later stage during the
implementation of the peace-keeping operation.
</P>
<P>
"The major task of the observers is to monitor the cease-fire,
standstill as well as the withdrawal of troops," he added.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
