<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Intention to Subvert New Wye Deal Detected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GAZA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian security agencies
have evidence that the Palestinian extremist groups Hamas and
Islamic Jihad had plotted to derail the newly signed revised Wye
agreement, according to a Palestinian security official.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinian security agencies are ready to ward off this
threat, Chief of Palestinian Preventive Security in West Bank
Colonel Gebriel Al-Ragoub said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
He described the signing of the new land-for-peace deal as "a
historic step," and expressed hope that dialog between the
Palestinians and Israel would lead to security and peace.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian police have arrested some 100 Hamas activists who
threatened to launch violent attacks on Israeli targets.
</P>
<P>
The new agreement triggered angry reactions among Palestinian
opposition factions.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the deal, Hamas spiritual leader Sheikh Ahmed
Yassin said on Saturday the Palestinian leaders "retreated and
retreated."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the opposition People's Front for the Liberation of
Palestine and the Democratic Front for the Liberation of Palestine
warned that the new agreement would have a negative impact on
their reconciliation dialog recently started in Cairo with Fatah,
the mainstay of the Palestine Liberation Organization led by
Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
