<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0014 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arab League Welcomes Palestinian-Israeli Memo on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Arab League on Sunday
expressed welcome to the memo for the implementation of the Wye
accord signed between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The agreement is "an important step on the road of the (Middle
East) peace process," Arab League Secretary General Esmat
Abdel-Meguid said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid underlined the importance of liberating every
inch of the occupied Palestinian territories and restoring the
legitimate rights of the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
He stressed the necessity of an honest implementation of the
agreement without procrastination, and the respect for the
timetable stipulated in the accord.
</P>
<P>
Palestinian National Authority Chairman Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Ehud Barak signed the revised Wye accord
early Sunday in Egypt's Red Sea resort of Sharm el-Sheikh.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Israel will, among other things, pull back
from another 11 percent of the West Bank in five months from
September and the Palestinians and Israel will begin the final
status talks after the first Israeli troop pullback in a few days.
</P>
<P>
Abdel-Meguid called on the Palestinian people to achieve
cohesion during this decisive stage of their struggle to realize
their hopes and aspirations, foremost the establishment of an
independent state with Jerusalem as the capital.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the chief of the 22-nation pan-Arab forum expressed
hope that the Syrian-Israeli peace talks will be resumed from
where they were left off.
</P>
<P>
The Syrian-Israeli negotiations came to a halt in early 1996
due to dispute over the Golan Heights captured by Israel from
Syria in the 1967 Mideast War. The two sides have expressed
readiness to resume their peace talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
