<HEADLINE> Simitis Urges Turkey to Help Improve Climate in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Greek Prime Minister Costas
Simitis Sunday called on neighboring Turkey to help improve the
climate of relations between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference in the northern Greek city of
Thessaloniki, Simitis said that Greece was exercising a policy of
peace and cooperation, and Turkey should examine its own line, its
own views, and finally make a move that would help to bring a
major improvement in the climate, the semi-official Athens News
Agency (ANA) reported.
</P>
<P>
As for Greece's earthquake aid to Turkey, he said that Greece
operated a principle of assisting other countries, especially
neighboring ones, when disaster struck.
</P>
<P>
Greece's principle was friendship and cooperation among peoples
and the earthquake in northwestern Turkey could not be viewed as
an opportunity, because that would make a mockery of Greece's
policy, the prime minister said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, Greece Sunday welcomed acceptance by
the European Union (EU) foreign ministers of its proposal that
Turkey should receive reconstruction aid after the earthquake from
the EU.
</P>
<P>
The aid will reportedly be nearly 200 million euros in the
form of grants and another 600 million euros in loans from the
European Investments Bank.
</P>
<P>
For years, Greece, which has a strained relations with Turkey,
has blocked the more than 1-billion U.S. dollars EU financial aid
to Turkey.
</P>
<P>
Greece has this week signalled it would support short-and
long-term aid being prepared by the EU in response to the
devastating August 17 earthquake in the neighboring country. 
</P>
