<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh's Central Bank Withdraws Notice From Local Bank </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh Bank, the country's
central bank, on Sunday withdrew its show-cause notice from the
board of directors of a private bank recognizing the management
under its chairman, who was reportedly forced to resign last
month, as the legal authority of the bank.
</P>
<P>
"Only a return of normalcy and restoration of confidence of the
public and deposition in the bank has now caused the Bangladesh
Bank to withdraw the notice dated August 27, 1999," said a central
bank order addressed to Mr. Zafar Ahmed Chowdhury whom the center
bank addressed as the "chairman of the board of directors" of the
United Commercial Bank LTD (UCBL).
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Bank notice, directing the board of directors of
the UCBL to refrain from participating in the bank's management
until further notice and asking why they should not be dissolved,
was issued one day after Akhtaruzzaman Chowdhury Babu, a former
director of the bank, reportedly stormed a board meeting of the
UCBL along with armed outsides and forced several board members
including Zafar Ahmed to resign.
</P>
<P>
The High Court later stayed the central bank's directive to the
board of directors of the UCBL following a prayer of the writ
petition filed by UCBL Chairman Zafar Ahmed and 10 directors.
</P>
<P>
"Bangladesh Bank notes that there was a failure of security in
the board meeting of the bank on August 26, 1999 resulting in
chaos and the resignation of several directors which were
retracted promptly," the central bank's withdrawal order said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, in a hurriedly-called press conference after the
Bangladesh Bank order, Zafar Ahmed said that "though late, the
central bank decisions has restored the people's confidence and
saved a private bank."
</P>
<P>
He demanded police action against Babu under the criminal
producer code "for the sake of security and growth" of private
sector in the country.
</P>
<P>
The UCBL has 79 branches throughout the country with a deposit
of 11 billion taka (about 220 million U.S. dollars), employing
more than 2,500 people, according to Zafar Ahmed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
