<HEADLINE> International Support for Independence of Palestine, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
said Sunday that there was great international support for the
creation of an independent Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
Arafat, who returned to Italy Sunday morning following the
signing of Saturday's peace agreement with Israel, said that he
had received "very important" declarations from "Europe, the
Japanese government, Russia, China and President Clinton"
concerning their support for Palestinian independence.
</P>
<P>
The President of the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) was
speaking at the annual industrialists' conference in the Italian
northern town of Cernobbio.
</P>
<P>
He said that action must be swift and decisive in order to
consolidate the peace process and international co-operation is
vital.
</P>
<P>
"The Palestinians want peace verbally and factually but time is
a decisive factor. If progress isn't tangible and immediate, the
enemies of peace will use this period to instill doubt about the
feasibility and benefits of peace," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
"The intervention of friendly nations is urgent, in particular
that of Egypt and its President, Mubarak, the U.S. President
Clinton, Europe and all the forces supporting liberty and peace,"
he continued.
</P>
<P>
"Palestinians remain committed to the process of reconstructing
infrastructure and the economy, in spite of the disaster inherited
from the Israeli occupation," Arafat said.
</P>
<P>
Arafat and Barak signed Saturday evening in Sharm el Sheikh on
the Egyptian Red Sea an agreement for the application of a
modified version of the Wye Plantation land-for-peace memorandum
signed on October 23 of last year, turning a further 7 percent of
West Bank territory over to Palestinian control and entailing the
release of 350 Palestinians held in Israeli jails.
</P>
<P>
The 70-year-old Palestinian leader has been shuttling backwards
and forwards to Italy over the last two days: he flew into Rome
Saturday morning from Gaza for a round of meetings with Italian
President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi and Premier  Massimo D'Alema; then
he flew out to Egypt in the afternoon for the signing ceremony
with Israel; he returned to Italy Sunday morning and is now
scheduled to fly back to Gaza in the early afternoon. 
</P>
</TEXT>
