<BODY>
<HEADLINE> OPEC Meeting to Support Production Ceiling Accord: </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The coming ministerial
meeting of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries
(OPEC) will support the production ceiling accord signed last
March to maintain the stability of oil market, said Omani Oil
Minister Mohammed al-Ramhi on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
"The conference of OPEC's ministers of petroleum to be held in
Vienna on September 22 will come out with resolutions to support
stability of the oil market and confirm the cuts of production
approved by the organization's member countries," al-Ramhi was
quoted by the Oman News Agency as saying.
</P>
<P>
OPEC members agreed in March to cut oil output by 1.7 million
barrels per day (bpd). Non-OPEC producers including Mexico,
Norway, Oman and Russia agreed to cut output by 400,000 bpd.
</P>
<P>
With these countries sticking to their quota observance, oil
prices have been rising ever since.
</P>
<P>
Al-Ramhi said Oman would take part in the Vienna conference,
which would evaluate the current oil market situation and elect a
new OPEC secretary-general.
</P>
<P>
The minister also praised a recent agreement reached in
Caracas, Venezuela, between the petroleum ministers of Saudi
Arabia, Mexico and Venezuela to maintain the March accord up to
April 2000.
</P>
<P>
The three ministers expressed their satisfaction with the oil
market's gradual return to stability and promised to maintain the
output cut accord after their meeting last week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethiopia Beefs Up Efforts to Curb Substandard </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ADDIS ABABA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Ethiopia will establish
six check points to control the inflow of substandard contraband
food and industrial products, the Ethiopian Standards Authority
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The check points will be established in the main ports of Bahir
Dar, Mekelle, Nazreth, Dire Dawa, Gambella and Awassa towns.
</P>
<P>
The authority urged the customs in various parts of the country
and all the concerned institutions to curb the inflow of
commodities that are hazardous to the public health and
detrimental to the national economy.
</P>
<P>
Currently, expired canned food and beverages as well as light
and heavy industrial products are being imported into the country
without the knowledge of the standards authority.
</P>
<P>
However, 234 state standards had been set up in the just-ended
fiscal year, the authority said, adding that efforts had been
intensified to set up Ethiopian standards for medicines and pepper
soon.
</P>
<P>
In collaboration with the associations of mechanical,
electrical and agricultural engineering, the standards authority
has finalized a study to put in place the new Ethiopian standards.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
