<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indians Ends First Day Polling Amid Tight Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Millions of Indians cast
their votes on Sunday for the first phase of five-stage general
elections, the third in four years, with moderate to heavy
turnouts amid a tight security.
</P>
<P>
President Kocheril Raman Narayanan, Congress President Sonia
Gandhi and senior officials of the caretaker government went to
the polls in their constituencies in New Delhi,
</P>
<P>
However, Atal Behari Vajpayee, leader of the Bharatiya Janata
Party (NJP) and the caretaker prime minister, is scheduled to file
his nomination as BJP candidate next Tuesday from Lucknow, capital
of the north Uttar Pradesh.
</P>
<P>
The pollings, which began from 0700 AM local time and
concluded at 0500 PM, passed off peacefully, if not for three
minor incidents, amid tight security and with an estimated turnout
of 45 to 50 percent in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
A 55,000 strong police force, assisted by some 5,000 central
para-military soldiers were deployed across the capital, where 45
polling stations had been identified as "hyper-sensitive" and 175
as "sensitive".
</P>
<P>
Police had also sealed the city's borders with neighboring
states and arrested a large number of "anti-social elements" in a
bid to ensure peaceful elections.
</P>
<P>
Electronic voting machines were used for the first time in all
seven constituencies in the capital and reportedly received an
enthusiastic response from the electorate.
</P>
<P>
Out of 8,668 machines, 139 were found faulty and were changed
before the start of the polls while three were replaced after the
polls began.
</P>
<P>
Things were not going on so smoothly in another 144
constituencies spread over 16 states and union territories.
</P>
<P>
In the south state of Andhra Pradesh, three people were killed
in poll-related violence between supporters of the contested
parties. The Central Election Commission is likely to order a
repoll in 60 polling stations in the area.
</P>
<P>
In the northwest state of Punjab, three people were reportedly
injured and police fired in air at a polling station while 12
people were hospitalized after consuming allegedly poison-laced
tea at another station.
</P>
<P>
However, an estimated 55 percent of the total electorate of
467,000 in the south states of Tamil Nadu and Karnataka exercised
their franchise in the polling, which was by and large peaceful.
</P>
<P>
In the state of Haryana which around the capital, between 59 to
62 percent of the 11 million electorate turned out at 15,457
stations to make a choice of 10 Lower House members out of a total
of 114 hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
Between 40 to 42 percent polling was recorded at 26
constituencies in the west state of Gujarat today, during which 35
untoward incidents were reported including 18 cases of bogus
voting and impersonation.
</P>
<P>
In the neighboring state of Maharashtra, around 56 percent
voters cast their ballot for 24 national parliament and 144 state
assembly constituencies peacefully.
</P>
<P>
Another four phases of elections have been scheduled to be held
on 11th, 18th and 25th of September and on October 3. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0029 </DOCNO>
