<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UK's Stonehenge an "Art Gallery": Physicist </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The standing stones at
Stonehenge and Avebury in Britain depict human faces just like the
stone statues found on Easter Island in the Pacific, a physicist
said in a British newspaper on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
The prehistoric standing stones at Stonehenge and Avebury, have
been the subject of speculation for generations. People have
variously argued that the stone circles were built by visiting
aliens or pagan worshippers and were used as an antiquated
calendar or for magical rites.
</P>
<P>
Terence Meaden, a former professor of physics, argues that
Avebury is "an art gallery" dedicated to a mother goddess figure,
according to the Independent on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Photographs show what could be human faces as well as sheep and
snakes in the stones at certain angles in certain lights, Meaden
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0031 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ruling Coalition Suffers Heavy Losses in German State </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN September 5 (Xinhua)-Germany's ruling Social Democratic
Party (SPD) lost sole control of two state parliaments after the
regional elections on Sunday, a loss that could endanger
Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder's sweeping reform package.
</P>
<P>
In the state of Saarland in west Germany, the SPD got 44.3
percent of the vote, down sharply from 49.4 percent in the last
election. Its major opposite, the conservative Christian
Democratic Union (CDU), won a tiny but clear edge with about 45
percent of the vote.
</P>
<P>
The CDU will take over the Saarland government from the SPD,
which had solely ruled the state for 15 years before the election.
</P>
<P>
And in the eastern Brandenburg state, the SPD suffered an even
heavier loss. Its vote dropped to about 39 per cent from 54.1
percent four years ago.
</P>
<P>
The CDU won 26 percent of the vote in Brandenburg, but the
bigger winner was the Democratic Socialism Party (PDS), the
successor to the Communists in former East Germany which won 24
percent of the vote on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
A fresh face that would emerge in the Bradenburg state
parliament was the rightwing extremist German People's Union
(DVU), which had won 5.3 per cent of the vote. The party won 13
percent last year in the state election in Saxony-Anhalt.
</P>
<P>
The DVU and other rightwing extremists, such as the Republicans
and the National Democratics of Germany, had won shocking
achievements in recent German regional elections, especially in
the east states.
</P>
<P>
Both in Saarland and Brandenburg, the Greens Party, Schroeder's
junior partner in Berlin cabinet, was not able to score more than
5 percent of the vote to hold a seat in the state parliaments.
</P>
<P>
The elections on Sunday shifted the balance in the Bundesrat,
the upper house of German federal parliament, against Schroeder's
cabinet.
</P>
<P>
Made up of representatives from the 16 German federal states,
the Bundesrat is able to veto legislature bills of the SPD, which
had lost majority after successive defeats in three state
elections.
</P>
<P>
Schroeder's ambitious reform package, projected to cut billions
marks of the budget by limiting social welfare spending, is afraid
by many to be blocked, since dozens of SPD lawmakers have openly
attacked the bill and already threatened to vote against it in
Bundestag, the powerful lower chamber of the parliament.
</P>
<P>
Analysts say the voters were disappointed in the SPD's poor
achievement in solving Germany's domestic problems since it gained
the power nearly one year ago. The reform package itself also
aroused skepticism both inside and outside the party. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0032 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> S. African President to Attend OAU Summit in Libya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, September 5 (Xinhua) -- South African President
Thabo Mbeki is scheduled to leave for Libya Monday to attend a
special summit of the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in
Sirte, media reports said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
During his forthcoming three-day visit to the north African
country, Mbeki will also attend a celebration in Libyan capital
Tripoli to mark the 30th anniversary of the revolution that
brought Muammar Gadaffi to power in 1969.
</P>
<P>
Mandated by OAU member states at a meeting in Algiers earlier
this year, the special summit will review the OAU's charter in
Sirte, a town near Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The review will form part of a broader re-examination of the
Africa's largest organization, its structures and effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
The proposed revisions to the charter are seen as an attempt to
 strengthen economic and other forms of cooperation among member
states.
</P>
<P>
The charter, signed in Ethiopian capital Addis Ababa in 1963,
already commits its signatories to promoting African unity and
solidarity, and to coordinate political, economic and defense
policies.
</P>
<P>
Mbeki will be accompanied by Foreign Minister Nkosazana Zuma,
senior officials from the presidential office and the department
of foreign affairs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Palestinian, Israeli Officials End Athens Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The Palestinian and Israeli
officials ended their fourth meeting in Athens Sunday with a
common declaration calling for close cooperation in fight against
terrorism.
</P>
<P>
In a common declaration, participants, which included former
Israeli Prime Minister Shimon Peres and Palestinian official
responsible for the Jerusalem issues, Faisal Al-Husseini,
condemned all forms of acts of terrorism and violence. Both sides
were determined to cooperate closely in an uncompromising fight
against terrorism, which would safeguard the peace process and
allow the two peoples to become an integral part of the Middle
East community.
</P>
<P>
The participants also recognized the Palestinian people's
legitimate right for self determination while the Palestinians
stated that their goal would be the establishment of an
independent democratic state alongside Israel.
</P>
<P>
The meeting, which began Thursday, decided to establish three
committees, an inter-parliamentarian committee, a civil society
and people-to-people committee and a political committee.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also decided that the steering committee composed
of representatives of both sides and of a representative of the
Greek Ministry of Foreign Affairs would monitor and report on the
implementation of what has been agreed upon in the declaration.
</P>
<P>
The meeting also endorsed the proposal advanced by the Greek
side to explore the possibility of close cooperation among Israel
and the Palestinian Authority and Greece in the preservation of
cultural heritages as well as in the protection of natural
resources and other environmental issues. Two respective
committees will be formed towards this end.
</P>
<P>
The Athens meetings were sponsored by Greece in order to foster
a climate of trust and seek viable and lasting solutions to the
Mideast problem.
</P>
<P>
The first such meeting took place in Athens in July 1997.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0034 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pro-Taliban Rally Condemns Kandahar Blast </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A large-scale rally was held
Monday in the southern Afghan town of Kandahar, demanding arrest
of those responsible for a bomb blast outside the residence of
Taliban supreme leader Mulla Muhammad Omar last month.
</P>
<P>
Some 10,000 people gathered at a mosque in central town and
condemned the blast, describing it a conspiracy of anti-Islamic
elements, sources from Afghanistan said.
</P>
<P>
The speakers, however, didn't accuse anyone of the explosion.
</P>
<P>
At least 10 people were killed and some 30 others injured when
a truck loaded with highly sophisticated explosive materials blew
off near Omar's house on late August 24. The Taliban leader
escaped unhurt in the blast.
</P>
<P>
Taliban have rounded up dozens of suspects in connection with
the blast, however, the Islamic militia have not blamed any one
for the incident, the sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
