<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0035 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 15:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Middle East Economic Briefs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The following is economic briefs
from Middle East countries:
</P>
<P>
ABU DHABI -- Monday's Arab daily "Al Hayat" predicts that the
economy of the United Arab Emirates (UAE) will pick up this year
thanks to the improvement of crude oil prices and the recovery
of non-petroleum sectors.
</P>
<P>
Banking sources expect a growth of over 5 per cent in gross
domestic product, as compared to a drop of 5.5 percent last year
due to the fall in oil prices.
</P>
<P>
The sources also anticipate that growth in the petroleum sector
alone will reach some 15 percent, to bring in about 22.43 billion
dollars this year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the UAE central bank expect that UAE gross domestic
product this year will amount to about 180 billion dirhams (US
dollar equals 3.67 UAE dirhams), as compared to 170 billion
dirhams last year, a growth of approximately 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Syrian Minister of Finance Khaled Mahyni has denied
reports that dropping gold prices have brought about a loss of
about 545 million Syrian liras (US dollar equals 50 liras) in view
of the circulation of about 25 tons of gold in the market.
</P>
<P>
Monday's "Al Hayat" quoted Mahayni as saying Syria's economic
policy has abandoned the idea of expanding total reserves ever
since the seventies, and has moved toward stable reserves.
</P>
<P>
CAIRO -- The final report issued by the Egyptian Ministry of
Tourism on the Tourism and Shopping Festival put the number of
tourists visiting Egypt at 445,273 from July 20 to August 20, as
compared to 369,089 tourists during the corresponding period in
1998.
</P>
<P>
Monday's Cairo daily "Al Ahram" says that average hotel
occupancy in the governorates participating in the 1999 festival
has also increased to 87.5 per cent, 20.7 percent higher than the
figure in 1998.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- The Syrian Ministry of Economy and Foreign Trade
and the Syrian Commercial Bank have placed at the disposal of
Syrian exporters 10 million dollars to improve their
competitiveness in Arab markets and to provide them with the
advantage of selling on credit to importers in Arab states.
</P>
<P>
TRIPOLI -- The Egyptian Commercial Attache in Tripoli Mustafa
Mekkawi has disclosed that a set of transactions are expected to
be concluded, covering diverse Egyptian commodities exhibited
in the Tripoli fair of African industries, which opened here
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
Participating in the fair are 13 African countries as well as
97 Egyptian companies.
</P>
<P>
DAMASCUS -- Chairman of the Federation of Syrian Chambers of
Commerce Ratib Al Shallah and President of the Federation of
Industry and Trade in Safakis, Tunisia, Mohamed Bin Abdulla
on Sunday signed an agreement to establish a commercial marketing
company to provide information and services to businessmen in both
countries.
</P>
<P>
Monday's "Al Hayat" says that the two sides have signed an
agreement for cooperation between the "fairs company" in Safakis
and the Syrian "fairs company" in order to benefit from each
other's distinguished relations with European and African states,
Gulf states and Federation of Independent States (former Soviet
Union). The two sides also examined the prospects of establishing
a company for animal fodder and another for cotton weaving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0036 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 15:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cyprus Welcomes Palestinian-Israeli Peace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Cypriot government Monday
welcomed peace agreement signed between the Palestinians and Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians and Israel signed on Sunday a revised peace
agreement with a view to implement the Wye Plantation peace accord.
</P>
<P>
"The government considers that every step in the direction of
peace in our region has a positive impact on the efforts to settle
the Cyprus issue," the Government Spokesman Michalis Papapetrou
said.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the Middle East peace process would move
ahead in the next months in a steady manner. 
