<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Netherlands to Modify Regulation On Abortion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Brussels, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Dutch government said on
Monday that it has decided to improve the regulation and
assessment of termination of 24-week pregnancy.
</P>
<P>
It can happen that a woman who is advised that her unborn child
has little if any chance of survival is unable to face the
pregnancy and asks her doctor for a termination, the government
said in a news release.
</P>
<P>
"In situations in which the child is and can never be viable,
the doctor is required to notify the municipal coroner of the
termination and to have the decision assessed by a peer group,"
the news release said.
</P>
<P>
Such an action is not a punishable offense and need not
therefore be appraised by the government, it added.
</P>
<P>
The regulations' second category concerns serious disorders as
a result of which "the child is not expected to survive for long
after birth and prevailing medical opinion gives it no hope".
</P>
<P>
In these circumstances, a late termination of pregnancy is
possible too, on grounds of an emergency situation and subject to
strict conditions, the government said.
</P>
<P>
However, such a situation remains a punishable offense in
principle, the government added.
</P>
<P>
The new release said the modifications were recently decided by
the Council of Ministers of the Netherlands. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
