<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0042 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> DPJ Candidate Opposes Amendment to Japan's Constitution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Takahiro Yokomichi, a candidate
from Japan's largest opposition Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ)
presidential election, said Monday the preamble and the war-
renouncing Article 9 of Japan's constitution should be left intact.
</P>
<P>
Yokomichi, also head of the DPJ executive council, strongly
criticized the suggestion by the party's Deputy Secretary General
Yukio Hatoyama that the pacifist Constitution be amended, Kyodo
News reported.
</P>
<P>
Hatoyama plans to include the issue in his campaign for the
September 25 election for DPJ presidency.
</P>
<P>
"If we play around with the text of the Constitution, there
will no longer be a limit to dispatching troops overseas and to
the exercising of the right to defend ourselves collectively,"
Yokomichi said in an interview with Kyodo News.
</P>
<P>
"There is historical significance of the preamble and Article 9,
and we should not touch them," Yokomichi said.
</P>
<P>
Article 9 of Japan's constitution bans the threat or use of
force as a means of settling international disputes.
</P>
<P>
The issue is sensitive within the DPJ as its members, who range
from conservatives to left-leaning lawmakers, have different
opinions on it.
</P>
<P>
Yokomichi, who is running along with Hatoyama against incumbent
leader Naoto Kan in the DPJ presidential race, also blamed
Hatoyama for saying it may be inevitable that the party will break
up as a result of the debate on amending the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
"I cannot understand how someone in a leadership position of an
organization can say such a thing," he added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0043 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Secretary of State Visits Vietnam </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, September 6 (Xinhua) -- U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright began a two-day working visit to Vietnam
Tuesday and held talks with Vietnamese government and party
leaders on bilateral relations and regional and international
issues of common concern.
</P>
<P>
After her arrival here earlier in the day, Albright held talks
with Vietnamese Deputy Prime Minister and Foreign Minister Nguyen
Manh Cam in the afternoon. She also paid separate courtesy visits
to Vietnamese Communist Party General Secretary Le Kha Phieu and
Prime Minister Phan Van Khai later.
</P>
<P>
During the meetings, according to the Press and Information
Department of the Foreign Ministry, the two sides exchanged views
on bilateral relations as well as regional and international
issues of mutual concern. They satisfactorily acknowledged the
steps of improvement in their relations since the two countries
resumed diplomatic relations in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Both sides, during these talks, recognized the importance of
the Vietnamese-U.S. Trade Agreement based on equality and mutual
benefits, which marks the normalization of the two countries'
socio-commercial relations.
</P>
<P>
Albright told a press conference on Monday evening that she and
the Vietnamese leaders had also discussed problems such as tracing
American soldiers missing in action (MIA) during the Vietnam War,
the human rights issue, and cooperation in fighting against drug
criminals.
</P>
<P>
Albright is scheduled to attend a ceremony on Tuesday morning
to receive four remains of American servicemen listed as MIA at
Hanoi's Noi Bai International Airport. The remains were found
recently by Vietnamese-U.S. joint search teams or the Vietnamese
side alone.
</P>
<P>
Albright will also visit the U.S. Consulate General in Ho Chi
Minh City, and meet with the city's Mayor Vo Viet Thanh and U.S.
businessmen in the city before leaving Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
She is accompanied by senior officials of the U.S. Department
of State and Ambassador to Vietnam Douglas Peterson.
</P>
<P>
Albright's visit to Vietnam is en route to the APEC
(Asia-Pacific Economic Cooperation) meeting in Auckland, New
Zealand.
</P>
<P>
This is Albright's second visit to Vietnam. Her first visit to
Vietnam was in June of 1997.
</P>
<P>
Vietnam and the United States normalized their diplomatic
relations in July, 1995, 20 years after the Vietnam War ended in
1975. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
