<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore SilkAir Crash Probe in Final Stages </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Investigations into the
Singapore SilkAir MI 185 crash which killed 104 people, have gone
into the final stages, Singapore Communications and Information
Technology Minister Yeo Cheow Tong said Monday.
</P>
<P>
In response to an inquiry of the latest developments on
investigations of the details of the crash, Yeo also told the
Parliament that investigations have not found a reason to blame
the captain of the flight for any disciplinary actions.
</P>
<P>
The Civil Aviation Authority of Singapore (ACAS) is satisfied
that there was no reason to ground the captain of the flight for
his disciplinary actions as the safety of the passengers were not
compromised, said Yeo.
</P>
<P>
He also added that investigations were conducted in line with
standards set by the International Civil Aviation Organization
(ICAO).
</P>
<P>
Although Singapore's airliners have excelled in the past in
light of international standards set by ICAO, they can not be
complacent and have to continue reviewing their practices, said
Yeo.
</P>
<P>
"The government will continue to participate actively in
investigations and extend its full cooperation," said Yeo.
</P>
<P>
Relatives of the air-crash victims have been asking the
authorities to fully investigate the cause of the tragedy in 1997
near Palembang, Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Latest media reports raised doubts over the flight captain's
disciplinary behavior as the investigations went on. 
</P>
</TEXT>
