<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Postal Money-Order Service to Open Between China and Kazakhstan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- China and the Republic of
Kazakhstan today reached an agreement on bilateral postal money-
order services.
</P>
<P>
Liu Andong, deputy director of China's State Post Bureau, and
Urazaly Yerazhanov, director general of the State Enterprise of
Postal Services of the Republic of Kazakhstan signed the protocol
here today.
</P>
<P>
Yerazhanov has been in Beijing attending the ongoing 22nd
Universal Postal Congress.
</P>
<P>
To date, China has signed postal money-order protocols with 22
countries, and Kazakhstan is the first CIS (Commonwealth of
Independent States) nation to sign such one with China.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, services for small-sum cash exchanges will
be mutually available in amounts up to 1,000 U.S. dollars, and
people in both countries will be able to remit their earnings
across the border via local post offices.
</P>
<P>
A total of 232 outlets offering international postal payment
services have been set up throughout China.
</P>
<P>
The bureau says that China will expand this service by opening
more outlets and signing similar protocols with other foreign
countries.
</P>
<P>
Furthermore, China will adopt advanced technology to simplify
procedures and include other related services such as settlement
payments. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
