<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Underground Home Built for Sutra-Engraved Stones </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The city government of Beijing
announced today that it will send 10,082 pieces of ancient stone
engraved with Buddhist sutras back to their original underground
home in order to preserve them.
</P>
<P>
The stone tablets were carved by Buddhist monks from the Sui
Dynasty (581-618) to the Ming Dynasty (1368-1644). In 1957, the
tablets were excavated from caves near the Yunju Temple in
Fangshan County outside of Beijing, and since then they have been
stored in a special temple warehouse.
</P>
<P>
Because the tablets have been eroding, the city government has
built an underground palace using modern technology and equipment
for these precious relics.
</P>
<P>
Now, visitors will have to go underground to see the stone
sutras which will be kept in a closed environment saturated with
nitrogen and kept at a constant temperature and humidity.
</P>
<P>
A grand ceremony to mark the event will be held at the Yunju
Temple on the morning of September 9, with people from both China
and abroad attending. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
