<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Americans Work Longest Hours Among Industrialized Countries </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Workers in the United States
spend more hours on job than those in other industrialized nations,
clocking up nearly 2,000 hours per capita in 1997, according to
the latest study of the International Labor Organization (ILO).
</P>
<P>
That means the Americans work two more weeks than their
counterparts in Japan where annual hours worked have been
gradually declining since 1980, the ILO said in the study released
here Thursday. But the working hours of 1,889 in 1995 in Japan are
still the second longest among the industrialized countries.
</P>
<P>
The ILO study examines 18 Key Indicators of the Labor Market (
KILM) including labor productivity, labor costs, unemployment and
underemployment and hours worked.
</P>
<P>
The long working hours of U.S. and Japanese workers contrasts
most sharply with those of European workers, who are logging
progressively fewer hours on the job, particularly in the
Scandinavian countries such as Norway and Sweden where hours spent
in work in 1997 were respectively 1,399 and 1,552 per year.
</P>
<P>
The ILO study also found that in spite of divergence in working
hours, the major industrialized countries are seeing convergence
on the labor productivity front.
</P>
<P>
On average, labor productivity growth in western Europe has
been increasing at a faster rate than in the United States,
according to the study. This suggests that the major competitive
challenge to current U.S. productivity dominance comes not only
from a reviving Asian economy, but also from the major European
economies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
