<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Cracks Over 40,000 Fraud Cases In 20 Years </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- More than 40,000 fraud cases
have been solved in China in the last two decades, Liang Guoqing,
vice procurator-general of the Supreme People's Procuratorate,
said here today.
</P>
<P>
"After untiring efforts against fraud crimes using legal
weapons, the Chinese government has effectively curbed the
increase," Liang said at a speech today at the 4th annual meeting
of the International Association of Prosecutors (IAP).
</P>
<P>
Dealing with the crimes of "fraud and corruption" is on the
agenda for academic discussions at the conference.
</P>
<P>
Liang admitted that China has faced great challenges in
fighting fraud in recent years, especially with the increasing
number of transnational frauds and organized fraud groups
penetrating the country.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that the number of foreign swindlers who
practised frauds and were arrested in China in 1998 was 10 percent
higher than in 1997.
</P>
<P>
"Recent years have also seen more Chinese criminal suspects who
absconded to foreign countries with huge funds obtained through
fraud," Liang added.
</P>
<P>
"The fraud rings and their members tend to use intelligent and
high-tech means to perpetrate crimes, which creates many
difficulties and higher challenges for cracking down on frauds,"
Liang pointed out, stressing that they not only have modern means
of telecommunications and transportation, but also use such high-
tech means as information networks.
</P>
<P>
According to Liang, China has built a comprehensive legal
framework in dealing with fraud crimes, with police, prosecutors
and judges each responsible for the investigation, prosecution and
adjudication of such cases, respectively.
</P>
<P>
Chinese police bureaus established specialized bodies in 1998
to focus on economic crimes, including frauds, the senior
prosecutor said.
</P>
<P>
"China's legislature has also amended many anti-fraud laws, as
swindlers have developed their craft in many new forms in recent
years," Liang added.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0077 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> End of Polar Adventure Era, Now its Science Led </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Scientific research
has taken the place of adventure and become the major task of
human activity in the polar region, according to Chen Liqi, chief
scientist of China's first arctic expedition.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the "Adventure Era" started early this
century with a number of pioneers embarking on explorations; and
then from the 1930s to 1950s came the "Heroic Era" which was
characterized by the challenging of mankind's endurance capacity.
</P>
<P>
"With more high-tech instruments and decreased risks, we have
now entered the era of scientific research," Chen said.
</P>
<P>
"It differs from the personal or folk style of adventure
because scientific research has specific goals and subjects, aimed
at ensuring that people can make use of the resources in the North
and South polar regions," he added.
</P>
<P>
"Adventure did contribute to the development of know-how about
the two regions but inevitably we have to say good-bye to it as a
form of activity, turning to further scientific research which
must be based on a higher starting point," Chen said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
