<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Emergency Systems for China's Maritime Oil Pollution </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua)-- Emergency fast reaction
services to tackle oil spills in China's seas will be established
early next year, according to Liu Dehong, deputy director-general
of the Chinese Maritime Safety Administration (CMSA).
</P>
<P>
He announced this at a seminar on International Oil Pollution
Compensation Funds (IOPCF) held here today.
</P>
<P>
The areas covered will include the northern seas, the East
China Sea, the South China Sea and the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
Liu explained that China now has an oil turnover volume of 200
million tons, which is increasing by 10 million tons annually,
with a resultant greater possibility of oil spill accidents.
</P>
<P>
"The emergency system will help prevent spilled oil from
diffusing and reduce the pollution damage as soon as possible," he
continued.
</P>
<P>
Earlier this year, the CMSA introduced emergency exercises for
oil spill accidents around Shanghai, Dalian and Shenzhen, three
major ports on China's east coast.
</P>
<P>
The director of the IOPCF, Mans Jacobsson, attended the seminar
and told delegates that the organisation was established under the
auspices of the 1971 Fund Convention, which was supplementary to
the 1969 International Convention on Civil Liability for Oil
Pollution Damage.
</P>
<P>
These two conventions were amended twice in 1992, in what are
known as the 1992 Civil Liability Convention and the 1992 Fund
Convention.
</P>
<P>
China has ratified the 1992 Civil Liability Convention, which
will come into force on January 5, 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0084 </DOCNO>
