<HEADLINE> Beijing Bidding Committee for 2008 Olympic Games Formed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Beijing officially launched
its bidding campaign for the Olympic Games as the city established
the Bidding Committee for the 2008 Games here on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The capital city of China, which failed in its bid for the 2000
Olympic Games, has submitted the application to the International
Olympic Committee (IOC) earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
The Beijing Bidding Committee consists of a total of 76 members,
with Beijing Mayor Liu Qi as President and Wu Shaozu, President of
the Chinese Olympic Committee (COC), as Exective President.
</P>
<P>
Chinese legendary volleyball coach Yuan Weimin, who is also
Deputy Minister of China's sports governing body the State Sports
General Administration, and Beijing Vice Mayor Liu Jingmin have
been named as administrative Vice Presidents of the Committee.
</P>
<P>
He Zhenliang, member of the IOC Executive Board, is the only
advisor of the Bidding Committee.
</P>
<P>
"It will not only be an honor for the people of Beijing and
China to have the Olympic flame ignited for the first time in
China whose population accounts for one fifth of the world's, but
a good chance to disseminate the Olympic spirit and boost the
Olympic Movement," Liu Qi said.
</P>
<P>
"Bidding for the Olympics is an arduous job with hope and
challenge," Liu said. "But with the support of all the Chinese
people, we are fully confident that we will win the bid."
</P>
<P>
Wu Shaozu said:"Beijing has its own advantage in bidding for
the Olympics. It's an ancient city with a history of 3,000 years.
And most importantly, in the past 10 years, it has built quite a
few sports facilities with international standard and summed up
rich experience of staging international competitions."
</P>
<P>
"COC will fully support Beijing's bid for the 2008 Olympic
Games," Wu said.
</P>
<P>
Beijing Vice Mayor Liu Jingmin said his city will improve the
conditions to meet the required standards of the IOC for staging
the summer Olympics. 
</P>
</TEXT>
