<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Fishery Sector Urged to Increase Output </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia Monday urged the
country's fishery sector to increase fish output to meet the
demand of the increasing population in the next decade.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Sulaiman Daud made the appeal when
launching the aquaculture code of practice in the northern state
of Pulau Pinang, Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that since Malaysia's population was projected to
increase to 28.41 million by 2010, the fishery sector would have
to boost the present annual fish output of 1.24 million tons to
1.93 million tons by that time, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said that for aquaculture, the government has targeted an
annual yield of 600,000 tons, a 450-percent increase from the
present annual output of 133,000 tons.
</P>
<P>
The minister was confident that the desired aquaculture output
to meet both domestic and export demand is achievable if there is
good balance between production and sound environmental
management.
</P>
<P>
He said the government, in this context, has adopted approaches
aimed at enhancing the quality of aquaculture products,
introducing guidelines for aquacultural development and practicing
the code of practice for aquaculture. 
</P>
</TEXT>
