<HEADLINE> Nigeria's Poll Gives President Obasanjo Pass Mark </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A poll found that a majority of
the respondents in Nigeria thought President Olusegun Obasanjo
had performed above average in his first 100 days in office.
</P>
<P>
The poll conducted last week by local newspaper The Post
Express said that among the 553 persons polled, 339 representing
61.3 percent said that the president had done well in addressing
the myriad of problems confronting Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
According to the poll results released by the paper on Monday,
164 persons or 29.66 percent do not think the president has done
well while 50 persons or 9.04 percent are indifferent.
</P>
<P>
Most of those who gave the president a pass mark praised his
handling of the fuel crisis which characterized the General Sani
Abacha era and continued till the handing over of the power by
the military to the new administration in May this year.
</P>
<P>
They also commended his administration's policies toward better
 telephone services, employment generation and the retirement of
military officers.
</P>
<P>
On the contrary, nearly all those who said that the president
had not done well criticized his tardiness in addressing the
electricity problem which has crippled many small and
medium-scale industries and made life painful for ordinary
Nigerians.
</P>
<P>
They also slammed the president for not moving decisively
against armed robbers and other social miscreants who have made
the nation's major cities unsafe for law-abiding citizens.
</P>
<P>
The local newspaper said that the nationwide poll sought an
assessment of the performance of the president by Nigerians of
all walks of life, including men and women of diverse political
persuasion and ethnic background. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
