<HEADLINE> Nigeria to Resume Troops Pullout From S. Leone </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Nigerian President Olusegun
Obasanjo said on Sunday the pullout of Nigerian troops from Sierra
Leone would resume next month.
</P>
<P>
The president said on a national television program marking his
first 100 days in office that he failed to agree with the United
Nations on keeping the peace keepers in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
About 1,200 Nigerian soldiers in the West African Peacekeeping
Force or ECOMOG was flown back last week. But Nigeria government
suspended the pullout following an urgent visit of Sierra Leonean
President Tejan Kabbah who called for the regional power to
re-consider its decision for the stability in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
Nigeria originally planned to withdraw its troops at a rate of
2,000 men per month and leave only a 1,000-strong contingent at
the end of the six- month pullout. The country has about 12,000
men in the 14,000-strong ECOMOG

force stationed in Sierra Leone.
</P>
<P>
President Obasanjo did not say whether the policy could be
reviewed if disarmament did not move as quickly as planned under
a July peace accord between Kabbah and rebels to end more than
eight years of civil war.  
</P>
