<HEADLINE> Malaysia's Sarawak State to Increase Rice Production </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's Sarawak State
plans to increase rice production to ensure 65 percent
self-sufficiency within the next five years, State Agriculture and
Food Industries Minister Adenan Satem said Monday.
</P>
<P>
To achieve the target, Sarawak is devising an efficient rice
production system incorporating latest technologies from the very
basic seed production to post harvest operations, the minister
said at a three-day seminar on "Commercial Rice Production in
Sarawak: Prospect and Challenges" in the state capital of Kuching,
Bernama news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He said that so far 804,470 hectares had been identified
suitable for wet paddy cultivation in the state and there were 10
potential granaries covering 128,000 hectares.
</P>
<P>
Although land for the wet paddy cultivation is abundant in
Sarawak only 57,000 hectares were cultivated with wet paddy
annually, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said the state government would consider various incentives
that could boost food production in Sarawak.
</P>
<P>
According to the state minister, the current rice production of
60,432 tons in the state only met 35 percent of the state's needs
and the other 65 percent or 114,500 tons had to be imported.
</P>
<P>
Last year Sarawak imported 114,500 tons of rice valued at 111
million ringgit (29.21 million U.S. dollars) and this accounted
for about 10 percent of the state's total food import bill, Adenan
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
