<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Jordanian King Kicks off Landmark Visit to Kuwait </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Jordanian King Abdullah Bin
Hussein left here Monday for a landmark two-day visit to Kuwait in
a bid to repair and restore bilateral ties to levels prior to the
1990-91 Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Accompanied by Queen Rania Al Hussein and a high-level
delegation, Abdullah is expected to hold talks with Kuwaiti Emir
Sheikh Jaber Ahmad Sabah to further cement ties, which had just
been normalized in March after 10 years of strains.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian Foreign Minister Abdul Ilah Khatib described the
visit as a "major development that will restore relations between
the two states to previous levels" before the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Kuwait severed its relations with Jordan as Amman sided with
Baghdad after Iraqi troops stormed into Kuwait in 1990, which
sparked the 1991 Gulf War.
</P>
<P>
The most important factor of Abdullah`s visit is to restore
bilateral political relations to previous peaks, Khatib said.
</P>
<P>
He also recalled that Jordan and Kuwait had enjoyed "strong
bonds on a reciprocal basis" over three to four decades before the
Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
After Abdullah took the throne in February, Jordan has been
cautiously following a policy to maintain friendly ties with all
Arab countries, including its powerful neighbor Iraq and Iraq`s
arch Arab rivals Kuwait and Saudi Arabia.
</P>
<P>
Abdullah said on many occasions that his kingdom will not
improve ties with one country at the expense of another.
</P>
<P>
Analysts in Amman believed Jordan has to strike a delicate
diplomatic balance between Iraq and Kuwait, which still saw each
other as enemy nearly 10 years after the Gulf crisis.
</P>
<P>
Currently, Jordan depends on Iraq as its only source of crude
oil under the U.N. oil-for-food program for Iraq, but the
debt-ridden kingdom has to eye the lucrative labor market in
Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Jordanian workers had remitted hundreds of millions of
U.S. dollars each year from Kuwait before they were expelled by
the emirate during the Gulf crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
