<HEADLINE> Lebanese PM Justifies Syrian Military Presence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese Prime Minister Salim
Hoss has justified the two-decade Syrian military presence in his
country when he met with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright during her visit to Beirut two days ago.
</P>
<P>
The Voice of the People radio Monday said Albright had raised
the issue of the presence of Syrian troops on Lebanese soil during
the talks.
</P>
<P>
Israel set up a self-declared security zone in south Lebanon
in 1985 with the claimed aim of protecting of its north from
Lebanese guerrillas' cross-border attacks.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon has been asking Israel to withdraw its troops from its
border enclave without any conditions.
</P>
<P>
"I told her that Lebanon differentiates between the Israeli
occupation of a chunk of the south and Syrian military
presence," Hoss was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
He asserted that Lebanon viewed the Syrian presence as
legitimate because it was requested by the late Elias Sarkis when
he was president of Lebanon in 1976.
</P>
<P>
The 35,000 Syrian troops, which were then called in to help
halt the country's 1975-1990 civil war, are still deployed across
the country ostensibly to help maintain the nation's post-war
stability.
</P>
<P>
But, the country's ultra-rightist flank of Christian community,
which is spearheaded by exiled former army commander Michel
Aoun, has been opposed to Syria's military presence in Lebanon.
</P>
<P>
"The Syrian forces will remain in Lebanon as long as the
Lebanese government deemed their presence necessary," Hoss added.
</P>
<P>
Albright made a unscheduled brief visit to Lebanon on Saturday
in the course of her Mideast tour, the first since Israeli Prime
Minister Ehud Barak took power from his hardline predecessor
Benjamin Netanyahu in July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
