<HEADLINE> Manila Pledges Steady Rice Prices </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine government will
work harder to keep the prices of rice and other basic commodities
steady, Philippine News Agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Edno Joson, head of the National Food Authority (NFA), said his
agency continues to sell rice at 14 pesos (one dollar is equal to
40 pesos) per kilo, and that he does not foresee any increase in
the near future.
</P>
<P>
"Our stocks remain sufficient to maintain the 14 pesos per kilo
consumer price," Joson said.
</P>
<P>
He added the NFA has deployed at least 45 rolling stores in
Manila alone, and is now setting up more such stores nationwide so
that a greater number of poor Filipinos can avail of low-priced
commodities.
</P>
<P>
Joson said the NFA, which is directly under the Office of
President Joseph Estrada, aims to set up at least 4,000 of these
stores to meet a self-imposed target of 10 percent of all
communities in the country.
</P>
<P>
"So far, we have set up some 2,500 of these stores. We are
monitoring the process of establishing more of these," he said.
</P>
<P>
These NFA rice stores offer basic commodities that are priced
20 percent lower than those sold in other outlets. Such strategy
has helped bring prices down, he added. 
</P>
