<HEADLINE> Efforts to Improve Employees' Rights, Benefits in HK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region government has adopted a progressive
approach in improving employees' rights and benefits to keep pace
with Hong Kong's social and economic development, a senior
official said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The drive is aimed at striking a balance between the interests
of employees and employers, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Addressing the opening ceremony of the department's "Know the
Employment Ordinance Week" on Monday, Matthew Cheung Kin-chung,
commissioner for labor, said that this approach has worked well in
the past and will continue to be adhered to in future.
</P>
<P>
Cheung noted that the Employment Ordinance (EO) had undergone
several major reviews and amendments since its enactment in 1968
to better protect employees' rights and benefits.
</P>
<P>
The more recent amendments included increasing an employee's
entitlement of paid annual leave from seven days to a maximum of
14 days according to his length of service, and strengthening of
maternity and employment protection.
</P>
<P>
"As for education and publicity work, we will take into account
the uniqueness of individual industries and arrange for specially
designed promotional activities for employees and employers to
have a better understanding of their rights and benefits as well
as obligations under the EO," he said.
</P>
<P>
Organized by the Labor Relations Promotion Unit of the Labor
Department, the "Know the Employment Ordinance Week" aims to
promote labor relations in Hong Kong by enhancing public
understanding of the Employment Ordinance.
</P>
<P>
Promotional activities such as exhibitions, seminars, quizzes
and a radio program will be organized from September 6 to 12.
</P>
</TEXT>
