<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 12:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Security Services Banned From Using </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, September 6 (Xinhua) -- In a landmark ruling,
Israel's Supreme Court Monday barred the security services from
using interrogation methods, which it ruled were tantamount to
torture.
</P>
<P>
The nine-judge panel decided that it was illegal for
Israel's Shin Bet security service to use those interrogation
methods, which have been inflicted on thousands of Palestinian
detainees.
</P>
<P>
``The court declares the Shin Bet does not have the
authority to shake a person, to force him into a (contorted)
position or to kneel in a frog-like position or deprive him
of sleep,'' the court said.
</P>
<P>
"The authority which allows the investigator to conduct a
fair investigation does not allow him to torture a person, or
treat him in a cruel, inhuman or degrading manner," the court
added.
</P>
<P>
The ruling overturned a decision made by a
government-appointed commission headed by a Supreme Court judge in
1987, which permitted the Shin Bet to use "moderate physical
pressure" against suspects.
</P>
<P>
Human rights groups estimate that some 850 detainees a year
are subjected to those interrogation techniques, which the Shin
Bet says should be used in order to prevent terror attacks.
</P>
<P>
The ruling came just a day after two car bombs exploded
Sunday in two Israeli cities, killing three people, presumably
the bombers, who apparently were trying to carry out terror
attacks.
</P>
<P>
Following the ruling, Israeli Deputy Defense Minister Ephraim
Sneh was quoted by Israel Radio as saying that ``limiting the
Shin Bet's (investigative) capabilities does not help protect
Israel's citizens in the reality in which we live.''
</P>
<P>
However, human right groups, that hailed the ruling as a
watershed, said that the "ticking bomb" cases are extremely rare
and the Shin Bet just systematically mistreated detainees to
extract information. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0114 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Pacific Army Management Seminar Opens in Singapore </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September (Xinhua) -- Army chiefs of Singapore and
the United States stressed here Monday at a regional seminar that
armies are in transition, changing from a cold war army to an army
for the 21st century in some profound ways.
</P>
<P>
Chief of Army of the Singapore Armed Forces Major General Lim
Chuan Poh and Chief of Staff of the U.S. Army General Eric K.
Shinseki made the point in their respective keynote speeches at
the opening ceremony of the five-day 23rd Pacific Armies
Management Seminar (PAMS XXIII).
</P>
<P>
The seminar, co-hosted by the Singapore Armed Forces (Army) and
the United States Army Pacific, is being attended by army chiefs
of regional countries as well as 105 delegates from 35 countries.
</P>
<P>
Army chiefs of 20 regional countries are in Singapore for the
four-day first Pacific Armies Chiefs Conference (PACC-I) on
September 5-8, 1999, with their discussions focusing on "changes
confronting the armies of the 21st centuries."
</P>
<P>
PACC-I opened here on Sunday and Singapore Deputy Prime
Minister and Minister for Defense Tony Tan Keng Yam gave a dinner
in honor of the participants.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the dinner, Tony Tan said, "Many countries are
recovering from the economic crisis and they will need a stable
environment to rebuild their economies and attract foreign
investments."
</P>
<P>
"The events of the past two years have clearly shown that the
security and economic prosperity of countries are inextricably
linked," he added.
</P>
<P>
The concurrently-held PAMS XXIII under the theme "Managing
Change for Armies in the 21st Century," is focusing on four topics
concerning the transforming of armies for the 21st century,
optimizing personnel in the 21st century, integrating technologies
into 21st century armies and defense diplomacy in the 21st century
environment.
</P>
<P>
Lim told the seminar that the fundamental driving force of the
change is the external geopolitical and security environment, the
domestic considerations, technology and knowledge with technology
being the biggest enabler of the change and knowledge being the
most important factor.
</P>
<P>
General Shinseki underlined that transformation is underway and
must continue and his army is going to promote the transformation
quickly and coherently and move forward professionally and
institutionally so as to build an army capable of meeting the
challenges of the early 21st century.
</P>
<P>
He also gave emphasis to the training of soldiers and the
development of competent, gifted leaders to meet the demands of
the uncertain world.
</P>
<P>
The PAMS has been held since 1978 in the United States and
other countries. PPACC-I evolved from the Chief of Staff
Counterparts Conference (CSACC) which was a U.S. initiative. The
last CSACC was held in the United States in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
