<HEADLINE> Philippines Should Speed Up Agricultural Modernization: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Philippine farmers will lose
heavily if the Philippine fails to modernize its agriculture
sector within the next three years, a senior official warned
Monday.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press briefing on the Agrilink '99, Agriculture
Secretary Edgardo Angara said that "the next three years will be
critical for us since 2002 is our deadline to be competitive
globally as tariffs on all products go down."
</P>
<P>
Angara said modernizing agriculture through the use of science
and technology will reduce the country's dependence on
importation.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines, for instance, imported 80 million pesos (about
2 million U.S. dollars) worth of rice last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
He added that the country may even opt to import substantial
volume of fish if it also failed to develop the marine sector.
</P>
<P>
The Agrilink '99, the biggest agri-business exhibition of its
kind in the country, is slated on October 7-9 at the Philippine
International Convention Center.
</P>
<P>
Angara said the government thus needs to strengthen the
farmers' capacity to compete globally through various
interventions.
</P>
<P>
These include the provision of post-harvest facilities and
farm-to-market roads, enhancing research and development and
improving packaging of products to make them attractive to the
export markets, he noted. 
</P>
</TEXT>
