<HEADLINE> Pak FM on Boycott of Election in Indian-Held Kashmir </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Pakistani Foreign Minister
Sartaj Aziz said Monday the boycott of so-called elections in
Indian-Held Kashmir by the vast majority of Kashmiris demonstrates
the complete alienation of the Kashmiri people from Indian rule.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said in a statement "the boycott has once again
demonstrated the Kashmiri rejection of the Indian occupation and
their determination to continue their struggle against the Indian
occupation and for their right of self-determination."
</P>
<P>
"This boycott also exposes India's false propaganda campaign
that the Kashmiri struggle is being sustained by infiltration from
outside," said the foreign minister.
</P>
<P>
The lowest ever turn out in these sham elections should once
again focus international attention on the reality of the Kashmir
issue, Aziz noted.
</P>
<P>
He said India cannot talk about its democratic credentials, as
long as it refuses to recognize the Kashmiri's democratic right of
self-determination.
</P>
<P>
"Not a single country in the world has ever accepted that the
territory of Kashmir is a part of India. Yet India has forcibly
occupied this disputed territory with the help of 700,000 troops,
who are carrying out a brutal repression of the Kashmiri people
and violating their basic human rights," he said.
</P>
<P>
Aziz congratulated the All Parties Hurriyat Conference (APHC)
in India-held Kashmir and its leaders for successfully organizing
the boycott of these illegal elections and for continuing their
political struggle for a U.N. supervised plebiscite to decide the
future of Kashmir. 
</P>
</TEXT>
