<HEADLINE> Manila Urged to Review Peace Accord With MNLF </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A Philippine Senate committee
on Monday called for a review of the 1996 peace agreement with the
Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF) to ensure peace in the
southern Philippine island of Mindanao.
</P>
<P>
Gregorio Honasan, who chairs the Senate peace, unification and
reconciliation committee, issued the call on the third anniversary
of the signing of the peace accord.
</P>
<P>
However, the accord has been marked by "an apparent discontent"
among the former Muslim rebels over its implementation, Philippine
News Agency (PNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
"President Estrada is duty-bound to comply with the commitment
contained in that peace accord," Honasan said during his regular
press conference.
</P>
<P>
"We must assure that whatever we had promised to the MNLF will
be satisfactorily complied with," he added.
</P>
<P>
"With the peace agreement, the nation has very well gained due
 recognition in the international community for ending more than
two decades of armed hostilities with Muslim rebels. Let us not
allow these gains to break down," he pointed out.
</P>
<P>
Honasan said the Estrada Administration should conduct a
critical assessment of how far the obligations stipulated under
the peace accord have been fulfilled and what are the other areas
that need to be strengthened.
</P>
<P>
"After three years since the peace pact was forged, we still
have to see real economic progress in the region that has been
isolated from the mainstream for quite a long time," he said.
</P>
<P>
"Even in terms of peace and order, we have a lot of work to
do," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said government's peace efforts will always remain shaky
and unstable unless there is a Comprehensive National Peace
Policy to guide government representatives in their obligations
with the rebel groups.
</P>
<P>
Honasan added that he is proposing the peace policy which also
seeks to institute necessary structural reforms -- socially,
politically and economically -- independent of political
patronage. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
