<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK Announces E-Commerce Week to Promote Local Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Hong Kong announced an "E-
Commerce week" from September 13 to 17 to help local companies
remain competitive in the e-commerce business era.
</P>
<P>
"E-commerce will be a major business trend in the future,"
Thomas Tang, executive director of the Hong Kong Productivity
Council (HKPC) told a press conference on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The readiness of a company in adopting e-commerce will be a
crucial factor in ascertaining the company's competitiveness in
the global market, Tang said.
</P>
<P>
According to Tang, there are about 112 million web users in the
world, over 10 million in Asia, and one million in Hong Kong.
Worldwide business transactions conducted via Internet reached 43
billion U.S. dollars in 1998, and are expected to exceed one
trillion U.S. dollars by 2002.
</P>
<P>
Tang said that a total of 17 industry associations pledged
their support towards the e-commerce initiative.
</P>
<P>
One of the major highlights of the e-commerce week will be the
launching of a mirror site of the productivity and promotion net (
PPNet), which was jointly set by the HKPC and the China
Productivity Centers Association in June this year, said W. C.
Keung, director of the HKPC.
</P>
<P>
The PPNet is a database network located in China to facilitate
information exchange between organizations in China's mainland and
Hong Kong in the areas of technologies, inventions, human
resources and management, business collaborations and productivity
news.
</P>
<P>
The mirror site to open on September 15 is a Hong Kong-based
information center supported by over 40 provincial and municipal
productivity centers in China, Keung said.
</P>
<P>
Other events of the e-commerce week will include the release of
the findings of a survey on e-commerce adoption in Hong Kong, a
contract signing ceremony of a joint project between the HKPC and
Sybase Hong Kong Ltd. to establish an Asian innovations and
technology solutions center, and a series of seminars targeting
various business sectors. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
