<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0135 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 13:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Gunned Down for Threatening Egyptian President </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian presidential guards
gunned down a man who threatened President Hosni Mubarak's life
with a knife on Monday, while the president was slightly injured,
the media reports said.
</P>
<P>
The reports quoted witnesses as saying that the man approached
Mubarak's car waving a knife as the president was waving to a
crowd through his car window in Port Said, a city 180 kilometers
northeast of Cairo, at the northern end of the Suez Canal.
</P>
<P>
Security guards opened fire and the man, who was not
identified, was hit several times, the witnesses said on condition
of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak was on his way to address a meeting in Port Said while
inspecting projects in the city. After the incident, he went on to
his meeting and delivered a speech as scheduled.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak has survived at least three attempts on his life.
</P>
<P>
In June 1995, Muslim militants fired on his limousine as it was
driving out of Addis Ababa airport of Ethiopia on the way to a
summit of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
His predecessor, President Anwar Sadat, was assassinated in
1981 by Islamic militants angered at his signing of a peace treaty
with Israel in 1979. Mubarak, who was Sadat's vice president,
became president after the assassination.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak plays a key role in mediating the peace talks between
Arab countries and Israel. He has helped the Palestinians and
Israel reach several peace agreements. The latest was the memo on
the implementation of the Wye accord, which was signed between the
two sides on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mubarak severely cracked down on Islamic militants who has
attempted since 1992 to topple the secular Egyptian government and
install a strict Islamic rule in the country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
