<HEADLINE> Canada Ends Probe of Mossad Use of Passports </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Canada has ended the probe of
suspected use of Canadian passports by Israeli secret service
Mossad, the country's Globe and Mail reported on Monday.
</P>
<P>
The foreign affairs source was quoted as confirming that the
investigation recently ended with the conclusion: There is
insufficient evidence to prove that Israel broke its pledge.
</P>
<P>
Canada began a second probe in 1997, when the Mossad was
alleged to break its pledge not to use Canadian passports in
covert operations.
</P>
<P>
Mossad was previously found to use purloined Canadian passports
in an assassination attempt on an Islamic official in Jordan.
</P>
<P>
Canadian Foreign Minister Lloyd Axworthy received Iron-clad
assurances from former Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
in 1997 that Mossad would no longer do it again, the newspaper
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
