<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0138 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Japan, Britain to Strengthen Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Japan and Britain Monday adopted
an action plan committing both countries to expand cooperation in
wide-range bilateral and international issues.
</P>
<P>
The plan, called "Action Agenda 21," was issued by Japanese
Foreign Minister Masahiko Komura and visiting British Foreign
Secretary Robin Cook after their meeting in Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
"The 21st century offers new opportunities for the special
partnership between the United Kingdom and Japan, a partnership of
shared interests and common challenges," the two ministers said in
the seven-page plan.
</P>
<P>
The two ministers agreed to promote "closer and more wide-
ranging cooperation" in 21 areas and to review and update them
regularly.
</P>
<P>
The 21 areas include exchange programs, trade and investment,
financial and economic issues, science and technology, conflict
prevention, nuclear nonproliferation and disarmament, development
assistance, the environment and international crime.
</P>
<P>
The action plan also calls for boosting exchange programs in a
broad range of areas, such as culture, sports and education, as
well as the exchange of legislators and government officials.
</P>
<P>
Cook, who arrived here earlier Monday for a three-day visit,
also met with Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi in the day.
</P>
<P>
During their meeting, Cook and Obuchi agreed to promote
exchanges between the two countries, with special emphasis on
exchanges between young people, Japanese officials said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
