<HEADLINE> Crowds Welcomed to Sydney </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, Septemper 6 (Xinhua) -- Rumours were dismissed on
Monday that Sydney would be booked out and overcrowded during next
year's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
Australian Tourism Minister Jackie Kelly said the biggest
threat to the goal of a 10 percent increase in international
visitors next year was widespread rumours that it was just too
much trouble, accordint to reports reaching here.
</P>
<P>
"There is myth and innuendo that Australia is oversold, full up,
booked up, you can't get there," Kelly was quoted as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Australian tourism industry is chasing the cash from an
extra 400,000 international visitors next year, which would
represent a 10 percent increase in arrivals to 4.7 million.
</P>
<P>
Kelly said people's travel and accommodation plans were tightly
bound into the event schedule, and just what accommodation and
flights were or were not available would not be known until the
ticketing was finalised.
</P>
<P>
"Once those tickets are out I think a lot of things will
crystallise, but at the moment they are being hoarded up and not
necessarily made available," she added.
</P>
<P>
Olympic ticket allocation has been thrown into disarray by a
row with the International Amateur Athletic Federation over the
track and field schedule. 
</P>
</TEXT>
