<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambia to Launch Electronic Cheque Clearing System </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A new electronic cheque
clearing system is soon to be launched in Zambia and all
commercial banks registered in the country will fully implement it
within the next two weeks, a Zambian newspaper, the Post, reported
Monday.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted Zambia Electronic Clearing House Limited
project manager James Kalengo as saying all work relating to the
new system had been completed, test runs had been successful and
the system would be launched on September 20.
</P>
<P>
"With the introduction of the new system, banking in Zambia
would be made much easier as zambia becomes one of the few African
countries to introduce this very advanced system," Kalengo said.
</P>
<P>
Kalengo said the initial aim of the new system was to reduce
risks with cheques and speed up the clearing process through an
automated approach.
</P>
<P>
Member banks would use computers and electronic sorting
equipment to improve cheque processing, allowing cheques to be
machine read.
</P>
<P>
He said all cheques for the new system had been printed and
supplied to all six participating commercial banks. The clearing
equipment was supplied by a South African company and two
processing centers had been set up in Zambian capital Lusaka.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
