<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0151 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China To Commemorate 2,550th Birth Anniversary of Confucius </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The opening ceremony of a week-
long series of activities to mark the 2,550th anniversary of the
birth of Confucius, China's ancient thinker and educator, started
today in the Confucius Temple in Beijing.
</P>
<P>
Among the events there will be a general knowledge test on
Confucius and his thought, a writing competition on the topic "
Confucius in My Heart", and also exhibitions about his life
experiences.
</P>
<P>
There will also be a huge party and several dance performances
at the temple from September 11 to 28, according to the organizer.
</P>
<P>
East China's Shangdong Province is now making preparations for
the 1999 International Confucius Cultural Festival in his birth
place of Qufu, beginning from September 26.
</P>
<P>
Zhou Qi, who is in charge of the organizing committee, said
that apart from the celebrations, lectures, academic seminars, and
discussions of the economy, trade, science, and technology, will
be held during the festival.
</P>
<P>
Confucius (551 B.C.- 479 B.C.) is regarded as a great thinker
and educator in Chinese history. Confucianism, the school of
thought that developed out of his ideas, has had a great influence
on China's political, cultural and social life for thousands of
years.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0152 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform the Only Way out for SOEs: Chinese President (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The only solution for the
problems facing the massive number of China's state-owned
enterprises (SOEs) is to further deepen the reforms with the core
aim of establishing a modern corporate system, Chinese President
Jiang Zemin stressed recently.
</P>
<P>
Jiang made the remarks during recent tours that took him to
Inner Mongolia, Sichuan, Hubei, Shanxi, Shandong and Liaoning,
where he paid visits to major SOEs and met with local officials on
SOEs reforms, according to the Outlook weekly magazine published
here today.
</P>
<P>
Jiang noted that through the reforms, SOEs must become
corporate entities which are autonomous in business and bear
responsibilities for their own losses.
</P>
<P>
He added that corporate reforms must be carried out in large
and medium-sized SOEs so that they would have an effective
management system, including a good stimulus and control mechanism.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed that great attention must be paid to the
leadership in SOEs, adding that it is very important to select
good senior managers.
</P>
<P>
As to the SOEs' heavy debts, surplus staff and social burdens,
Jiang said these problems must be solved gradually in accordance
with the principles of the market economy, instead of using the
old "big pot" methods.
</P>
<P>
Jiang stressed the need to adjust the strategic structure and
layout of the state-owned economy, which demands that the
production capacity of some traditional industries be reduced and
that enterprises with backward equipment, that wastes resources
and produces heavy pollution, are eliminated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0153 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Loan Scheme Helps Poor College Students </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- College freshmen in China who
lack the funds to do pay their own tuition this year will still
have an opportunity to go to learn: the Chinese government began
offering loans to financially-strapped college students, today's "
China Education Daily" reports.
</P>
<P>
According to the paper, in Beijing, 17 students from Qinghua
University and Beijing University have been granted a total loan
of 482,000 yuan from the Construction Bank of China, which started
providing loans for poor college students from July 8.
</P>
<P>
Each student can receive between 2,000 yuan to 50,000 yuan in
loans and are required to pay it back after they complete their
studies.
</P>
<P>
College students in southwest China's Chongqing Municipality
are required to pay half of the interest on the government loans
within four years of graduation. Chongqing is one of the eight
cities which has launched the new government loan project. The
other seven cities are Beijing, Shanghai, Tianjin, Shenyang,
Nanjing, Wuhan, and Xi'an.
</P>
<P>
This was the direct result of an experimental loan system for
poor students which allows a 50-percent discount on interest and a
four-year repayment period after graduation.
</P>
<P>
The scheme has been jointly introduced by the People's Bank of
China, the Ministry of Education, the Ministry of Finance, and
will be administered by the Industrial and Commercial Bank of
China. It was launched as the new academic year began last week.
</P>
<P>
In east China's Jiangxi Province, ten high school graduates who
have received the college matriculation notice recently received
loans from the Bank of China Jiangxi branch, which is the first of
this kind in the province, says the paper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Reform the Only Way out for SOEs: Chinese President (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
As the macro-economic situation and the state coffers allow,
Jiang said the banks might be asked to increase their reserves to
write off bad loans, which would be spent on promoting mergers and
settling bankruptcy cases among large and medium-sized SOEs.
</P>
<P>
He noted that those SOEs satisfying set conditions should be
allowed to swap their debts with state-owned banks for equities to
be held by their asset management companies, which have been
established recently to manage the banks' bad loans.
</P>
<P>
Jiang also mentioned the need to allow more SOEs the
opportunity to raise funds from the capital market.
</P>
<P>
Noting that one of the most important and difficult jobs in
deepening the SOEs reform is to create new jobs for laid-off
workers, Jiang stressed that local governments must provide the
necessary funds.
</P>
<P>
He promised financial support from the central government to
the middle and western regions and old industrial bases, which do
not have the means to re-employ the laid-offs.
</P>
<P>
The president said efforts should be made to encourage laid-off
workers to start their own businesses or be employed by non-state-
owned sectors.
</P>
<P>
Jiang called for further efforts on the part of the government
to restrict its role in SOEs, taking a non-interfering role in
their operations.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, he said SOEs should also change their
attitudes and not continue to rely on the government. Instead,
they should adapt to the needs of the market and seek their
survival and prosperity through market competition.
</P>
<P>
The president expressed his satisfaction over the general
situation of SOEs reform and their performance, citing statistics
which show a remarkable increase in enterprise profit and tax
revenues in the first half of the year.
</P>
<P>
He concluded that the government's policies in SOEs reforms
have been proved correct and that the goal of the reform is
completely attainable if such policies are implemented to the
letter and advantages are fully taken of the SOEs assets,
equipment, technology and other elements. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
