<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary At 0800 GMT, September 6 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG -- South African President Thabo Mbeki is
scheduled to leave for Libya Monday to attend a special summit of
the Organization of African Unity (OAU) in Sirte, media reports
said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
Mandated by OAU member states at a meeting in Algiers earlier
this year, the special summit will review the OAU's charter in
Sirte, a town near Tripoli.
</P>
<P>
The proposed revisions to the charter are seen as an attempt to
strengthen economic and other forms of cooperation among member
states.  (SAfrica-OAU-Summit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Prime Minster Massimo D' Alema said Sunday that
in the light of an investigative report, the government would push
the allied nations for more answers to the mysterious crash of an
Italian DC-9 passenger plane 19 years ago.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by Rome investigating judge Rosario Priore
last week, indicated that the crash off the island of Ustica near
Sicily killing all 81 on board was not an accident nor due to a
bomb aboard, but that the airliner might have been hit by
crossfire in a battle between warplanes. (Italy-Allies-Crash)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS -- The United Nations Security Council said on
Sunday it was planning to send a mission to Jakarta to discuss
with Indonesia how to deal with the violence in post-ballot East
Timor.
</P>
<P>
The council met Sunday night on the deteriorating situation in
the territory following the August 30 ballot on its future,
especially after the announcement of the ballot result Friday. (
UN-Indonesia-Call)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
JAKARTA -- Nearly 190 United Nations staff in East Timor will
be temporarily relocated to Australia, according to a statement
from the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET) published here Monday
noon.
</P>
<P>
The relocation will include 36 U.N. volunteers, 75 civilian
officers, 72 international staff and two staff members of the
UNHCR (U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees).
</P>
<P>
"UNAMET intends to bring its temporary relocated personnel back
to East Timor as soon as the security situation permits," the
statement added. (East Timor-UN-Relocation) 
</P>
