<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Dagestan Building Blast Toll Rises to 36 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The number of people killed in
the August 4 bombing of a residential building in Buinaksk, a city
in Russia's Dagestan republic, has risen to 36, the Itar-Tass news
agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
The powerful blast demolished a five-story apartment building
in a military compound, killing 14 people instantly. Fifty of the
injured remain hospitalized, Tass said, quoting a spokesman with
the local emergencies ministry.
</P>
<P>
The explosion also badly damaged two nearby buildings and
smashed windows throughout the complex.
</P>
<P>
Search and rescue operation continues at the site, where at
least 10 people are still believed to be under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials blamed the Saturday night car bomb attack on
Islamic militants. A second bomb in another car was found and
defused Sunday in the military housing complex, they said.
</P>
<P>
First Deputy Interior Minister Vladimir Kolesnikov said the
bomb blast was directly linked to an incursion Sunday by militants
who crossed the border from Chechnya and seized four villages. An
estimated 1,500 federal troops were sent to the Novolaksky region,
located 65 kilometers northwest of Buinaksk, to counter the
incursion.
</P>
<P>
The militants were said to have Russian police totally
surrounded in the village of Novolaksky. Federal forces used tanks
and mortars to attack the militants, whose numbers were estimated
at 2,000 men. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
