<HEADLINE> Share Prices Move Higher in Tokyo on Wall Street Surge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Stock prices closed higher in
Tokyo Monday, boosted by a surge on Wall Street last Friday.
</P>
<P>
The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues on the First
Section of the Tokyo Stock Exchange rose 126.52 points, or 0.72
percent, from last Friday's close to end at 17,756.51.
</P>
<P>
The broader-based Tokyo Stock Price Index (TOPIX), covering all
First Section issues, gained 15.08 points or 1.01 percent to 1,512.
08.
</P>
<P>
Turnover on the major section declined to 450.52 million shares
from 465.03 million shares last Friday.
</P>
<P>
Sakura Bank was the day's volume leader.
</P>
<P>
Investors were wary of taking new positions ahead of Thursday's
release of Japan's gross domestic product (GDP) for the April-June
period, traders said.
</P>
<P>
Market players expect the second-quarter GDP data to show a
small contraction, while the first-quarter GDP growth over the
previous quarter has been revised to a real 2.0 percent.
</P>
<P>
Even if the GDP figures are worse than expected, investors are
still likely to buy stocks, a dealer said.
</P>
<P>
Weaker-than-expected GDP data will stir expectations that the
government will be forced to take additional powerful measures to
boost the economy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Export-oriented high-tech blue chips were up, supported by
Friday's favorable performance on Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
Of the issues listed on the First Section, losers outnumbered
gainers 646 to 541 despite the overall gain in the Nikkei index,
with 149 issues closing the day unchanged. 
</P>
</TEXT>
