<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economists Pessimistic About Zambia's Economic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, September 6 (Xinhua) --Barclays bank's analysts have
doubted whether the economic growth target set by Zambian
government for this year will be hit.
</P>
<P>
The Quarterly Economic Review for the second quarter available
here Monday said the economy has not experienced any growth in the
year to date and prospects for the remaining months are not
brighter.
</P>
<P>
The government early this year projected a real economic growth
of four percent.
</P>
<P>
The report indicates the sale of mines, a good harvest and
reduced tariffs for the manufacturing sub-sector were supposed to
have played a major role in attaining the government goal.
</P>
<P>
However, the sale of mines were further delayed after the
pullout of a prospective strategic partner, Codelco, the Chilean
copper mining firm.
</P>
<P>
Results from the farming community have showed unexpectedly
lower harvest due to late fertilizer supply and bad weather.
</P>
<P>
"Large debt burdens, reducing local order books, pressure from
zambia revenue authority and demands for wage and salary
increments all add up to a serious situation," the review notes.
</P>
<P>
The review says that available statistics indicate total sales
volume slumping by 11 percent for the first five months of this
year, compared with the same period in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Investment pledges have also reduced to 71 million U.S.
dollars in the first half of this year from over one billion
dollars in the same period of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"This low level of investment pledge is of concern and the
situation will not change until the regional economy perks up and
investor confidence is restored through the stabilization of the
domestic economy," the review says. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
