<HEADLINE> Russian Air Force Pounds Militants in Dagestan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Russian air force jets made
nearly 40 sorties of air strikes on rebel positions in Dagestan on
Sunday, the Interfax news agency reported Monday.
</P>
<P>
Su-24 light bombers and Su-25 attack planes bombed and fired
rockets at Islamic extremists around the villages of Karamakhi and
Chabanmakhi, Interfax said, quoting sources with the Russian
Defense Ministry.
</P>
<P>
In addition, reconnaissance An-30 planes also flew over the
Novolakskaya district, which was captured by rebels from
neighboring Chechnya, a breakaway Russian republic.
</P>
<P>
The militants have captured the town of Novolakskoya and the
villages of Chapayevo, Sushiya, Akhar, Novoluki, Tukhchar and
Tamiyakh, Each of the villages was surrounded by hundreds of
armed militants, Interfax said, citing Russian military sources.
</P>
<P>
Large Russian federal units have not yet moved into the
district or Makhachkala, the sources say.
</P>
<P>
About 2,000 militants have amassed around the village of
Borozdinskaya on the Chechen-Dagestani border, the local law
enforcement agencies said.
</P>
<P>
In a related development, the number of people killed in the
Saturday night car bomb attack, which demolished a five-story
apartment building in a military compound in Buinaksk, Dagestan,
has risen to 40, Interfax said.
</P>
<P>
Of the 120 people injured in the blast, 58 have been
hospitalized, 22 have received medical aid on the spot and
released.
</P>
<P>
Search and rescue operation continues at the site, where at
least 10 people are still believed to be under the rubble.
</P>
<P>
Russian officials blamed the attack on Islamic militants. A
second bomb in another car was found and defused Sunday in the
military housing complex, they said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
