<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Habibie Says He Takes Responsibility for What is Happening in E. Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Amid criticism over the
situation in East Timor, Indonesian President B.J. Habibie
reaffirmed here Monday that he would take responsibility for what
has happened in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
"I am responsible for what has happened in East Timor," Habibie
said in a response to a question from journalists after a
consultative meeting with legislators at the House of
Representatives (DPR).
</P>
<P>
Habibie also stressed that the Indonesian government would keep
struggling to create peace and calm the situation in East Timor
during the post-ballot and transitional period as arranged by the
New York agreement.
</P>
<P>
He said he had long talks with U.N. Secretary General Kofi
Annan this morning, and because the two parties' have different
views, they will have further talks Monday night.
</P>
<P>
"What we have achieved right now is the fact that we have a
transparent, peaceful ballot (in East Timor). Don't take that for
granted," he said.
</P>
<P>
Habibie conducted a consultative meeting with House leaders
after a majority of the East Timorese rejected an autonomy package
in the August 30 direct ballot.
</P>
<P>
The situation in East Timor has been tense since the
announcement of the ballot results on September 4. The results
showed that over 78 percent of the voters supported East Timor's
independence from Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said a total of 145 people were killed in the
past two days and tens of thousands fled to some provinces of
Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
On Sunday, several Indonesian senior ministers including
Foreign Minister Ali Alatas and Defense Minister/Commander of
Armed Forces Wiranto visited Dili, capital of East Timor, and held
talks with officials of the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET),
local religious leaders and leaders from pro-integration and
pro-independence groups. They discussed the security situation in
East Timor and other issues related to the future of the
territory.
</P>
<P>
Early Monday, the U.N. Secretary General's special envoy for
East Timor arrived in Jakarta, capital of Indonesia. He is
expected to meet President Habibie and Foreign Minister Ali Alatas
to discuss the situation in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, was integrated into
Indonesia in 1976, but the move has never been recognized by the
U.N.
</P>
<P>
In January this year, the Indonesian government proposed to
give wide-ranging autonomy to East Timor. In May, the U.N.,
Indonesia and Portugal signed an agreement on the holding of a
direct ballot in East Timor to decide the territory's future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0173 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chirac Calls East Timor Situation Unacceptable </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, September 6 (Xinhua) -- French President Jacques Chirac
called the situation in East Timor "absolutely unacceptable," as
anti-independence militiamen are ruling the territory with terror
after a majority of East Timoris voted for independence last week.
</P>
<P>
Chirac made the statement during a telephone conversation with
Portuguese President Jorge Sampaio on Sunday, said Agence France-
Presse.
</P>
<P>
Chirac also said that France provides a total support to the
efforts of the United Nations Security Council aimed at ending the
violence in the former Portuguese colony, occupied by Indonesia
since 1975.
</P>
<P>
At least 145 people have been killed by pro-Indonesian
militiamen in East Timor since last Friday when the result of the
U.N.-sponsored referendum was announced, according to reports from
Dili, capital of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The International Red Cross said that 23,000 East Timoris are
taking refuge in the houses of the organization.
</P>
<P>
The U.N. Security Council decided on Sunday to send a mission
to Jakarta to pressure Indonesia to stop the violence in East
Timor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
