<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0174 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Singapore Gold-medallist Fails Dope Test </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SINGAPORE, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A Singapore swimmer who won
gold in last month's South East Asian Games has failed a dope test,
according to an official at Singapore National Olympic Council (
SNOC) Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 13-year-old Nicolette Teo, who is asthmatic, tested
positive for terbutaline, a substance commonly found in medication
for the illness, the official said.
</P>
<P>
Terbutaline is on the list of stimulants banned by the world
swimming body Fina although its use is permitted if an athlete
declares it before a drug test.
</P>
<P>
Teo set a new Under-14 national record for the 200 meters
breastroke at the games in Brunei last month. After her win, she
received the routine test for all winners where she declared
ventolin, a medication she had been using for more than ten years.
</P>
<P>
The SNOC has not made a final decision to her offence. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
