<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0179 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Backs Cote d'Ivoire's Bid for Next UPC: Premier </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Premier Zhu Rongji
said here today that China supports Cote d'Ivoire's bid to host
the next Universal Postal Congress (UPC) and wished it success.
</P>
<P>
Zhu made the remarks in a meeting with Daniel Kablan Duncan,
prime minister of Cote d'Ivoire, who arrived in the Chinese
capital Sunday to attend the ongoing 22nd UPC.
</P>
<P>
Extending him a warm welcome, Zhu said the Chinese government
emphasizes the importance of the current UPC.
</P>
<P>
"Thanks to the concerted efforts of all parties the congress
has run smoothly," he said, adding that he knew it would be a
complete success and contribute further to the development of the
world's postal services.
</P>
<P>
The premier noted that relations between the two countries have
witnessed steady and healthy growth since the establishment of
diplomatic ties 16 years ago. "In recent years especially,
cooperation in many fields has expanded and deepened," he added.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese government highly appreciates the Cote d'Ivoire
government's adherence to the "one China" policy and its support
to China's reunification cause," Zhu said.
</P>
<P>
According to him, there is a solid foundation for bilateral
friendship and broad potential for economic and trade cooperation.
</P>
<P>
"The governments and peoples of both countries share the common
aspiration of further consolidating bilateral cooperation," Zhu
said, adding that through joint efforts bilateral ties would have
a new look in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Duncan said Cote d'Ivoire is thankful for China's assistance in
its economic development, and is willing to further expand such
cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He also thanked the Chinese government for its support to Cote
d'Ivoire's bid to host the 23rd UPC.  
</P>
</TEXT>
