<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.N. Officials in East Timor Relocated to Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Nearly 190 United Nations
staff in East Timor will be temporarily relocated to Australia,
according to a statement from the U.N. Mission in East Timor
(UNAMET) published here Monday noon.
</P>
<P>
The statement said the decision was taken following the
uncontrolled violence that erupted in Dili, capital of East Timor,
and other parts of East Timor.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET has decided to temporarily relocated a number of its
staff to Darwin, Australia, the statement said, adding that the
movement will be assisted by the Australian government which will
provide aircraft for this purpose.
</P>
<P>
The relocation will include 36 U.N. volunteers, 75 civilian
officers, 72 international staff and two staff members of the
UNHCR (U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees).
</P>
<P>
"UNAMET intends to bring its temporary relocated personnel back
to East Timor as soon as the security situation permits," the
statement added.
</P>
<P>
UNAMET comprises 280 civilian police, an international staff of
241 and 420 U.N. volunteers.
</P>
<P>
At a press conference here Monday, the U.N. Electoral
Commission of the East Timor Popular Consultations issued a
statement, saying the August 30 direct ballot in East Timor was
procedurally fair and in accordance with the New York Agreements,
signed by the U.N., Indonesia and Portugal.
</P>
<P>
"There can be no doubt that the overwhelming majority of the
people of this troubled land wish to separate from the Republic of
Indonesia," the statement concluded.
</P>
<P>
The ballot showed that 344,580 voters or 78.5 percent chose
independence against 94,388 voters or 21.5 percent preferring
wide-ranging autonomy
</P>
<P>
According to the Antara News Agency, Comoro market in West Dili
sub-district was set on fire Monday morning by a group of
unidentified people.
</P>
<P>
On Monday morning, there was no sight of vendors selling
vegetables, fruits, rice, garments and other daily necessities.
They usually display their wares in the market.
</P>
<P>
There was no sight of public transportation. Motorized vehicles
were not seen roaming the roads in Dili while the residents
started again to flock to the East Timor police headquarters along
with their belongings to seek safety.
</P>
<P>
At least 4,000 East Timorese started flooding the hills
surrounding Dili Monday morning to seek protection, Antara said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the sound of fired guns continued to be heard from
Sunday night till Monday morning, coming from various parts of
Dili.
</P>
<P>
A number of houses, included four houses belonging to
pro-independence leaders, were seen ablaze in Dili.
</P>
<P>
According to Kompas daily, a total of 145 people were killed in
East Timor since the announcement of the direct ballot results on
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
In New York, the Security Council Sunday night issued a
presidential statement, condemning the violence in East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The statement asked the Indonesian government to take steps to
prevent further violence.
</P>
<P>
In Jakarta, President B.J. Habibie met with Speaker of the
House of Representatives Harmoko on Monday to discuss the issue on
East Timor. No details were disclosed.
</P>
<P>
East Timor, a former Portuguese colony annexed by Indonesia in
1976, has been seen by the U.N. General Assembly as a
non-self-governing territory. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
