<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Central Chinese City Bans Use of Car Horns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Changsha, capital of China's
Hunan Province, has banned the use of horns by motor vehicles on
24 of its downtown streets as of September 1.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the number of motor vehicles has
increased rapidly and there are now about 220,000. Before the ban,
horns could be heard almost 24 hours a day and there were plenty
of complaints about noise pollution from local people.
</P>
<P>
The city government recently passed a regulation on noise
pollution by motor vehicles saying that drivers are not allowed to
use their horns in residential and school areas and in commercial
centers.
</P>
<P>
Other restrictions are on the use of flashing lights or sirens
except in special cases, and flashing lights only from 11:00 p.m.
to 6:00 a.m.
</P>
<P>
Violators will be fined and if they accumulate a certain number
of penalties, they will be forced to stop driving and to take
classes on rules of the road.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
