<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Modern Technology Being Used to Protect Chinese Relics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists are
using modern technology from chemistry, physics, biology and other
fields to restore mottled murals, fragments of sculptures, broken
cups and bowls, and other old cultural relics.
</P>
<P>
Modern technology has been used since the 1960s to help protect
Chinese cultural relics, and, especially in recent years, to
reduce the harm done by humidity, pollution, and bacteria,
according to relics restoration specialists.
</P>
<P>
The 45,000 square meters of murals in the Mogao Grottoes at
Dunhuang in Gansu Province, northwest China, have been blurred or
become moldy for various reasons, so specialists at the Dunhuang
Academy developed a chemical bond to fix the murals, with special
tools.
</P>
<P>
Meteorological and environmental observation posts have set up
on the top of and inside the grottoes to monitor sunlight, wind
currents, precipitation, temperature, and humidity in the grottoes.
An environmental data bank is also being established at the
academy to provide information.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists in Shaanxi Province, also in the northwest, have
restored a bronze chariot from the Qin Dynasty more than 2,200
years ago in one of the most complicated restoration projects in
China.
</P>
<P>
The provincial museum of Guangdong in south China has developed
the country's first air filtration and purification system to
protect valuable paintings and books.
</P>
<P>
According to the State Cultural Heritage Administration,
cultural relics preservation specialists have developed various
technology to protect wooden buildings, stone inscriptions, murals,
and sculptures, to remove the rust from metal relics, to clean
textiles and papers, and to prevent moth and mold damage.
</P>
<P>
Archaeologists also know that some ancient relics are difficult
to preserve with modern technology. To them the earth can be
better than the most advanced museum for the time being.
</P>
<P>
So, more than 8,000 stone tablets with Buddhist scriptures will
be buried at the Yunju Temple in suburban Beijing on September 9,
after having been unearthed for more than 40 years. The weather
and air pollution have greatly damaged them and archaeologists are
waiting for more advanced technology to be found to help solve
their problem in the future.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
