<HEADLINE> Chinese President Leaves Thailand for Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PHUKET, THAILAND, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Chinese President
Jiang Zemin left here on Monday for Australia, ending his five-day
state visit to Thailand.
</P>
<P>
Princess Sirindhorn saw him off at the airport.
</P>
<P>
During his stay in the kingdom, Jiang held separate meetings
with King Bhumibol Adulyadej, President of the National Assembly
Wan Muhammad Nor Matha, President of the Supreme Court Pintip
Sucharitkul, Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai, Privy Councilor Prem
Tinsulanonda and former Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh.
</P>
<P>
He also delivered a speech on Sino-Thai relations and China's
policy towards Southeast Asia at Bangkok's Thailand Cultural
Center.
</P>
<P>
Jiang said China and Thailand will establish a more friendly
and closer relationship of all-round cooperation on the basis of
the existing friendly ties in the next century.
</P>
<P>
Jiang met representatives of overseas Chinese both in Bangkok
and the southern province of Phuket, the second stop of his visit.
</P>
<P>
After the Australia visit, Jiang will head for New Zealand to
attend the seventh informal meeting of leaders of the Asia Pacific
Economic Cooperation and pay a state visit to the island country.
</P>
</TEXT>
