<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines' Inflation Rate Lower in August </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- The Philippines' year-on-year
inflation rate slowed down to 5.5 percent in August from 5.7
percent in July mainly due to steady food rate, the National
Statistics Office said Monday.
</P>
<P>
The August figure brought the nation's inflation rate in the
first eight months of this year to 7.7 percent, well within the
government target range of 8 percent to 9 percent for the whole
year, the office said in a report issued here.
</P>
<P>
The office noted that the inflation rate for food remained at
3.2 percent, unchanged from the previous month, although higher
rates were posted in the prices of fish, 7.5 percent from 7.3
percent, and fruit and vegetables, 4.3 percent from -1.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
The unchanged food inflation rate was contributed to the lower
rates in the prices of rice, 2.9 percent from 3.5 percent, corn,
-4.4 percent from -2.3 percent, cereal preparations, 3.3 percent
from 3.9percent, dairy products, 3.1 from 3.3 percent, and eggs,
4.9 percent from 7.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the office said, the rate for clothing slowed down
to 5.5 percent from 5.7 percent, housing and repairs, 9 percent
from 9.3 percent, fuel, light and water, 5.9 percent from 6
percent, and services, 10.3 percent from 10.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
According to the office, the country's month-on-month inflation
rate in August rose by 0.3 percent, compared to 0.2 percent
registered for July. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
