<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0201 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Why China Is Doing Research In Eastern Arctic </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SNOW DRAGON SHIP, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A Chinese scientist
has explained why China chose the eastern part of the Arctic Ocean,
which has been ignored by humans for 100 years, for its first
Arctic Expedition.
</P>
<P>
Chen Liqi, chief scientist on the expedition, says that most
countries have focused on sea areas close to Europe and North
America but that China looked at eastern region because it has a
greater impact on China. It is covered with very thick ice and is
hard to enter and little data is so far available because of its
proximity to the U.S. and Russia.
</P>
<P>
The 56-day survey will fill this gap and provide fairly
valuable information about how the region will affect global
climate changes.
</P>
<P>
Russia and the U.S. opened some formerly forbidden zones in
the mid 1990s and decoded a great deal of classified data, which
was favorable to China's Arctic research, Chen says. With 15 years
of Antarctic research, his country has been able to train a large
number of polar researchers and establish its own polar research
system to support this first Arctic Expedition.
</P>
<P>
In 1996, China joined the International Arctic Science
Committee, which requires every member to do substantial research
and to contribute to the Arctic Pole sciences development.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0202 </DOCNO>
