<HEADLINE> Security Council Urges "Concrete Steps" by Indonesia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council said on Sunday it was planning to send a mission
to Jakarta to discuss with Indonesia how to deal with the violence
in post-ballot East Timor.
</P>
<P>
The council met Sunday night on the deteriorating situation in
the territory following the August 30 ballot on its future,
especially after the announcement of the ballot result Friday.
</P>
<P>
The majority of East Timorese, numbering some 800,000, voted in
favor of breaking ties with Indonesia, which has ruled the half-
island territory since 1976 after the withdrawal of the former
ruler Portugal.
</P>
<P>
Violent acts, in which anti-independence militias are believed
to be involved, have inflicted life losses on civilians and have
threatened the security of the U.N. Mission in East Timor (UNAMET),
which organized and conducted the ballot.
</P>
<P>
Security Council September president, Arnold Peter van Walsum,
of the Netherlands, said the mission would consist no more than
five members and they are expected to depart on Monday, though the
members are not decided yet.
</P>
<P>
The mission would discuss with Indonesia "concrete steps to
allow the peaceful implementation of the ballot result," according
to a press statement issued by the president.
</P>
<P>
"The Government of Indonesia has welcomed this intention," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The council "condemned in the strongest terms the intensifying
violence in East Timor" and "underlined once again the
responsibility of the Government of Indonesia to guarantee peace
and security in East Timor, the safety and security of all UNAMET
staff, local staff and premises," the statement added.
</P>
<P>
Indonesia is responsible for peace and security in East Timor
during the ballot and in its transition to independence, according
to the U.N. mediated agreement between Indonesia and Portugal on
May 5. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
