<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Strings Changes for Ethnic Tujia People (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGSHA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Xiuhua Mountain Hall in the
city of Zhangjiajie in central China's Hunan Province is a
masterstroke accomplished by Chen Chuhua and Gong Daoxiu, a couple
of ethnic Tujia background, through life-long dedication.
</P>
<P>
The hall, the first household-based museum built for Tujia
people, holds several thousand pieces of folk handiwork belonging
of the Tujia people.
</P>
<P>
With a population of 5.8 million, the Tujia live mainly in the
mountains of western Hunan Province, southwestern Hubei Province,
and eastern Chongqing Municipality. In Hunan alone, there are 1.8
million Tujia people.
</P>
<P>
The Tujia long led an extremely miserable life because the
places where they lived featured harsh natural conditions and a
social order dominated by bandits.
</P>
<P>
The waterwheels, looms, oil mill utensils, and other farm tools
in the museum remind people of the harsh past lived under the
Kuomintang rule before when the People's Republic of China was
founded.
</P>
<P>
The hall also stores a number of luxury items belonging to well-
off families of Tujia background, including chairs and cupboards
bearing fine engravings, and brocades, which serve as a testimony
to the heavy oppression previously suffered by ordinary Tujia
people.
</P>
<P>
Now, the Tujia have become their own masters since liberation
in when the last group of bandits were crushed, said the husband,
Chen Chuhua. In the early 1950s Chen was a youngster enrolled in a
local drama troupe where he began to learn more about the culture
of the Tujia people.
</P>
<P>
Great progresses have been made in economic growth, social life
and cultural development in the western part of Hunan Province,
where the poor population has been dropping sharply year by year
since China initiated its reform and open-up drive in 1978.
</P>
<P>
Earth-shaking changes have taken place in the lives of 900,000
Tujia people living in Zhangjiajie, now a popular tourist
destination, and a growing number of them have moved from mountain
caves into high-rise flats with modern home appliances.
</P>
<P>
Chen Chuhua's own prize-winning miniature garden, featuring a
design called "skiff having left 100,000 hills," is representative
of the Tujia people now advancing toward a comfortable life, and
his design is among the many exhibits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Museum Strings Changes for Ethnic Tujia People (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Though still living in the mountains, the Tujia have been
brought closer to the outside world with the completion of more
railways, highways, and the airport at Zhangjiajie. Many of them
are now good businessmen, according to Chen.
</P>
<P>
"But Zhangjiajie, where Tujia people have lived for generations,
is losing its features with the rapid disappearance of its unique
traditional arts like suspended houses, and only a small number of
traditional items have been placed in my hall," Chen said sadly.
</P>
<P>
He said he planned to build a group of suspended houses near
his hall in a bid to protect them from completely disappearing and
also to attract more tourists.
</P>
<P>
Chen's museum hall is constructed in traditional Tujia
architectural style, and has become a must-see item for tourists
in the region, receiving about 500 people daily during the height
of the tourist season.
</P>
<P>
The hall opened in 1997, and has won the support of the
Zhangjiajie city government. When direct air service from
Zhangjiajie to Hong Kong was inaugurated early this year, Chen
Chuhua, was specially invited by the city government to visit Hong
Kong.
</P>
<P>
Many of the items collected at the hall are now also used as
samples by Zhangjiajie and other areas of western Hunan to develop
tourist souvenirs.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jun, the couple's son and also a Chinese language and
literature graduate of Xiamen University, has chosen to return
home and manage the hall.
</P>
<P>
"It is a lot more backward here than it is in coastal areas,
but I can find a broader space to continue study and improve
myself," said the junior Chen.
</P>
<P>
Chen Jun has pledged that he will enhance the value of the
museum by using the exhibits for research into the history of the
Tujia people to realize his pursuits and those of his people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
