<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unforgettable Experience at UNDP (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Seventy-five-year-old Wei
Yuming, former vice minister of foreign economic cooperation,
remembered clearly what happened when he visited the United
Nations Development Program (UNDP) 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
As an official in charge of China's foreign assistance, Wei was
leading a Chinese delegation on a visit to the UNDP in 1978, at
which time he told the UNDP administrator that China was ready to
accept foreign aid, breaking a 20-year taboo.
</P>
<P>
Shocked by Wei's remarks, the UNDP official could not believe
his ears and asked the interpreter to translate again. When they
finally understand what was meant, the administrator promised to
take the proposal into consideration and visit China the next year.
</P>
<P>
"I can remember every details of the scene," Wei told Xinhua in
a recent interview. "Before that I had pondered the question over
and over again -- why can't China, a developing nation, accept
foreign aid?"
</P>
<P>
Wei's trip to the UNDP ushered in a new era in China's
cooperation with the outside world. Prior to that, China was only
a contributor to the international community, not an acceptor.
</P>
<P>
For 20 years after the Soviet Union stopped its assistance to
China in the 1960s, China refused virtually any kind foreign
assistance, but did contribute money to the UNDP and other
international bodies constantly during this period.
</P>
<P>
Wei said his feeling that China should accept international aid
grew stronger after China again refused international
contributions of about 100 million US dollars following the
cataclysmic Tangshan earthquake in 1976 that claimed 240,000 lives.
</P>
<P>
"Our country is not so rich, why can't we accept international
aid?" Wei asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Unforgettable Experience at UNDP (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
But all that changed after 1979. Within the first five years
after that year, the UNDP offered 100 million US dollars of
assistance to China, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
Assistance from the UNDP has added up to some 500 million US
dollars so far for more than 840 projects in China involving
agriculture, industry, energy, telecommunications, transportation,
health care, education, finance, taxation, social security,
poverty alleviation, women's development, economic restructuring,
and the utilization of overseas investment.
</P>
<P>
"This effective cooperation between China and the UNDP has
helped expand bilateral ties between China and international
organizations on a mutually beneficial basis, introduced new
technology, and trained specialized professionals for China," Shi
Guangsheng, minister of foreign trade and economic cooperation (
MOFTEC), said at a seminar last week.
</P>
<P>
"With limited capital, the UNDP has played a unique role in the
China's reform and opening drive and economic construction of the
country that has a vast territory and a huge population," he said.
"This fully demonstrates that the UNDP's assistance is effective."
</P>
<P>
China has been implementing the policy of both giving and
accepting international assistance since 1979, Wei said.
</P>
<P>
Other international bodies such as the UN Children's Fund and
the UN Food and Agricultural Organization, have followed suit. The
UN Children's Fund, for instance, cooperated on a total of 150
projects in China with aid of 300 million US dollars.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0213 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Brief History of China's National Flag </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- China's flag, the Five-Star
Red Flag, flies over Tian'anmen Square in the heart of the Chinese
capital and in front of government and commercial buildings and in
schoolyards
</P>
<P>
The Chinese are so familiar with it that every child knows that
the late Chinese leader Mao Zedong personally hoisted the flag for
the first time over Tian'anmen and announced the founding of the
People's Republic of China on October 1, 1949.
</P>
<P>
Few people, however, know that the flag was selected by members
of the Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC)
from 2,992 suggestions and Mao Zedong removed the proposed hammer
and sickle, the symbol of communism, from the final, as a sign of
greater democracy and national unity.
</P>
<P>
The time was 1949, when the Communist Party of China had seized
power from the corrupt Kuomintang regime, who then fled to Taiwan.
Between June and September of that year, the CPPCC met in Beijing,
then known as Beiping, to establish a government. Many issues were
discussed, and one was the new national flag.
</P>
<P>
People from all over sent in their own ideas to the political
advisors who discussed it and submitted their final candidate to
Mao. On the evening of September 25, he made the final changes.
</P>
<P>
During the struggle against the Kuomintang, the Party had
always held the banner of democracy and unity high and the one
large and four small stars against a red backdrop indicated that
the CPC wanted a coalition among all anti-Kuomintang forces and
ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
On September 27, the CPPCC passed a resolution making the Five-
Star Red Flag the national flag, saying that it symbolized greater
unity among the revolutionary people of China.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Liansong worked as a secretary with a local news agency in
Shanghai when he submitted the winning design. In 1950, Zeng was
given five million yuan in the old currency for his design, or
about 500 yuan (60 U.S. dollars) in today's currency. He was also
invited by the central government to stand on the Tian'anmen
Rostrum to watch the parade during New China's first anniversary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0214 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Popular Chinese TV Series Now Available in Tibetan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XINING, September 6 (Xinhua) -- Tibetans living in China, many
of whom do not speak Mandarin, can now watch a popular TV series
based on the classic novel "Outlaws of the Marsh" dubbed in
Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
This is the fourth of the most famous classic novels - "Journey
to the West", "Romance of the Three Kingdoms", and "Dream of the
Red Chamber" being the others - to be made into a TV series and
translated into Tibetan.
</P>
<P>
Yang Jijia, a director, says that the Tibetan language TV
series has been popular in the Tibet Autonomous Region and in
Qinghai, Sichuan and Gansu provinces, where a large number of
Tibetans live.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, an ethnic language film and TV drama
translation center in Qinghai has been working on dubbing films
and TV plays into ethnic languages. It translates films and TV
series into languages like Tu and Mongolian and has translated 100
films and 60 documentaries on science and education into Tibetan.
</P>
</TEXT>
