<HEADLINE> Italy to Push Allies to Answer Ustica Crash Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Italian Prime Minster Massimo D'
Alema said Sunday that in the light of an investigative report,
the government would push the allied nations for more answers to
the mysterious crash of an Italian DC-9 passenger plane 19 years
ago.
</P>
<P>
The report, released by Rome investigating judge Rosario Priore
last week, indicated that the crash off the island of Ustica near
Sicily killing all 81 on board was not an accident nor due to a
bomb aboard, but that the airliner might have been hit by
crossfire in a battle between warplanes.
</P>
<P>
The judge said it has been ascertained that there were at least
six fighter planes in the area, two French and four American,
including two F-104s near the airliner, and that an unidentified
plane, possibly a Libyan MIG warplane, appeared next to the DC-9
not long after it took off.
</P>
<P>
Given the results of such a lengthy investigation, D'Alema said
it was the duty of the government to press the allied governments
and NATO for any and all information that would help arrive at the
truth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
