<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> United, Powerful China Vital to Overseas Chinese, Scholar Says </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 6 (Xinhua) -- A united, powerful and
prosperous China is vital to the interests of overseas Chinese,
said a university professor here.
</P>
<P>
This is a shared feeling of numerous Chinese Canadians, who are
busy preparing unprecedented large-scale parades in celebrating
the 50th anniversary of the People's Republic of China.
</P>
<P>
Dr. B.N. Cham, chairman of the Confederation of Toronto Chinese
Canadian Organizations, expressed to Xinhua their deep-rooted
emotions for a respected China.
</P>
<P>
"Nobody will look up to you, if you are too weak and
indifferent in defense of your own interests," said the 63-year-
old professor of York University.
</P>
<P>
He lambasted the idea of splitting China into "two countries"
being preached by Lee Teng-hui in Taiwan.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese people suffered enough in old China under the so-
called "political pluralism," which proved nothing more than death
and poverty resulted from dogfights of warlords, the professor
said angrily.
</P>
<P>
"Warlords and political pluralism harmed overseas Chinese as
well, for you can imagine the humiliation overseas Chinese felt in
those days, when the rift-torn China was considered inferior and
the Chinese were rejected even entry into restaurants or cinemas
of the white," Cham said.
</P>
<P>
Since the founding of the People's Republic of China in 1949,
Cham said, the overseas Chinese have for the first time enjoyed a
feeling of self confidence and respect in the world.
</P>
<P>
He found himself irresistibly attracted by historical events
and theory of the revolution in the mainland of China. He read
works not only by Chinese leaders, but also by famous foreigners.
</P>
<P>
A "China craze" arose in the wake of the historic handshake of
Chairman Mao Zedong and U.S. President Richard Nixon and a second
wave of "China craze" came after China opened its door to the
outside world, Cham continued.
</P>
<P>
He was carried away by the China wave and in 1979 made his
first home visit to Puning County, Guangdong Province,-- still a
poor and backward place, the professor said.
</P>
<P>
But great changes overwhelmed Cham in his later home visits. "
Just see those newly erected magnificent buildings along the
streets of the same township," he said excitedly.
</P>
<P>
Cham envisages broad prospects for China in the next century
with stronger national defense and higher economic development
level.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0243 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Survey Highlights Sharp Income Disparity in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, September 5 (Xinhua) -- Most young workers
recently surveyed see an America in which there are sharp
disparities in income and opportunity.
</P>
<P>
The national survey of nearly 800 American workers between 18
and 34 found that there are many unmet needs among workers despite
the fact that the country is enjoying the lowest jobless rate in
almost 30 years and more than 19 million jobs created since 1991.
Many of them believe corporate America has failed to share the
rewards of success.
</P>
<P>
Commissioned by the AFL-CIO, the U.S. national federation of
labor unions, the survey was conducted by Peter D. Hart Research
Associates and released at the weekend.
</P>
<P>
Six-two percent of workers from 25 to 29 say employees fall
short when it comes to sharing profits with employees. By the time
they reach their 30s, young workers have come to view the economy
as one that fails to adequately reward all who contribute to its
success: 70 percent of workers from 30 to 34 say the most
important goal for the economy is to "make sure everyone, not just
CEOs, gets their fair share."
</P>
<P>
Young workers without degrees feel more insecure about the
future. The are facing a host of financial and economic pressures
that many college graduates are escaping. According to the survey,
49 percent of those without degrees are far more likely to worry
often about their income falling behind the cost of living, not
having enough money for retirement, being unable to afford an
education for their children, having more debt than they can
handle and health expenses they can't afford.
</P>
<P>
Three-fourth of today's young workers in the United States do
not have college degrees. This "forgotten majority" is in a
disadvantageous position because, according to the U.S. Labor
Department, the country's new economy is creating high-skilled,
highly-paid jobs, but most require a college degree. Among them
are computer engineers, database administrators, desktop
publishers, medical assistants and securities and financial sales
people.
</P>
<P>
While 71 percent of young college graduates have full-time,
permanent jobs, only half of young workers without degrees have
standard employment; the rest are working in part-time, temporary
or other substandard arrangements.
</P>
<P>
Also according to the survey, only 39 percent of young workers
without degrees are covered by employer-provided health insurance
and only 36 percent have a retirement plan with employer
contributions.
</P>
<P>
While two-thirds of young college graduates say they are
earning enough to save for the future, 51 percent of young
nongraduates say they are earning just enough or not enough to pay
the bills. Only 36 percent of them earn at lease 20,000 U.S.
dollars a year, compared with 68 percent college graduates who
earn more than this sum.
</P>
<P>
The study concluded that a new generation is entering the work
force with high hopes that are quickly replaced by
disillusionment. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0244 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Wants China in the WTO: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, September 5 (Xinhua) - Britain said on Sunday it wanted
to see China in the World Trade Organization because Beijing had a
major role to play in ensuring long-term strength and stability in
the global economy.
</P>
<P>
"We want to see China in the WTO for China's benefit, for our
benefit and for the benefit of world trade," British Trade
Minister Richard Caborn said in a statement issued shortly before
his six-day visit to China.
</P>
<P>
"Membership would ensure that China's trade partners enjoy
improved market access and a stable environment for investment and
trade. It would also provide China with more secure access to
global markets," he said.
</P>
<P>
Caborn's scheduled visit to China, which begins on Monday, is
expected to promote Britain's bilateral trade and investment with
China.
</P>
<P>
"The UK is now the sixth largest global investor in China and
by far the leading European investor with British companies
involved in more than 2,000 joint ventures," Caborn said.
</P>
<P>
"UK companies recognize that China is a market for long-term
investment, not easy short-term profits, and most are pleased with
their business achievements in China," added the trade minister.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0245 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Redknapp out of Poland Decider </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
The injury kept the Liverpool captain out of England's 6-0
drubbing of Luxembourg but coach Kevin Keegan had been hoping the
midfielder would be fit enough to play against Poland on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
England must win in Warsaw to ensure a play-off place in the
European Championships.
</P>
<P>
The news is a blow to Keegan, who is staring at a lengthening
injury list which already contained David Seaman, Darren Anderton,
Sol Campbell and Rio Ferdinand.
</P>
<P>
Inspirational playmaker David Beckham has a hamstring problem,
while Tony Adams has a dead leg and Kieron Dyer was substituted at
half-time following a knock and cramp.
</P>
<P>
Keegan, who hopes all three will be fit again by Wednesday,
said: "They have all received treatment and we are hopeful about
their progress. David is very bullish about his own fitness."
</P>
<P>
The good news for Keegan is that Paul Scholes, who scored a hat-
trick against the Poles at Wembley, is back from suspension.
</P>
<P>
Chris Sutton's foot injury has cleared up and with 19-year-old
striker Michael Owen proving himself back from injury with a
sensational last-minute goal at Wembley, Keegan has plenty of
permutations to unlock the Poles.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile Dyer, who says he hopes Keegan's decision to
substitute him at half-time against Luxembourg means he is being
saved to face the Poles, says his debut was the best day of his
life.
</P>
<P>
"I've never heard that kind of reaction towards me from a crowd
before.
</P>
<P>
"It nearly brought tears to my eyes. It was unbelievable. I
think it was when I set up Alan Shearer for his hat-trick goal
that they were shouting `There's only one Kieron Dyer.'
</P>
<P>
"Wembley was everything what I expected and more especially
with the crowd giving me a standing ovation when I walked around
the pitch at the start of the second half."
</P>
<P>
"Stuart Pearce said to me before the game `If you bring the way
you train onto the pitch, you'll be the best player today' and I
did just that," he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
