<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Security Council Meeting on East Timor </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
UNITED NATIONS, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The United Nations
Security Council late Sunday began discussing how to deal with the
violence in East Timor since the announcement of a ballot on the
future of the territory.
</P>
<P>
The U.N.-conducted ballot on August 30 turned to be in favor of
East Timor independence from Indonesia with only 21.5 percent of
voters wanting it to stay within Indonesia while enjoying special
autonomy.
</P>
<P>
Western reports said many East Timorese were killed in two days
after the ballot result was made public on Friday EST.
</P>
<P>
Some members of the international community would like the U.N.
to send peace-keeping forces to East Timor, but U.N. officials
said they hope that Indonesia will take the responsibility of
maintaining peace and security there according to the May 5
agreement between Indonesia, Portugal and the U.N..
</P>
<P>
The closed-door meeting began at 5:15 pm EST with a council
statement expected tonight, sources said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0247 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Indonesia Wins Four Badminton Titles </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Indonesia took the both singles and men's and mixed doubles.
Dane pair Helene Kirkegaard/Rikke Olsen beat their Indonesian
rival Elysa Nathanael/Deyana Lomban 15-12, 15-7 to take the women'
s doubles title.
</P>
<P>
In the men's singles, world number nine Taufik Hidayat defeated
his compatriot Budi Santoso with straight sets 17-14, 15-12. The
18-year-old Taufik had to fight neck-and-neck with his senior from
the beginning. Both players rallied from the baselines before
performing their jumping smashes.
</P>
<P>
Taufik said he was satisfied with the win because he always
lost to Budi, who lost to Malaysian Yong Hock Kin in last year's
final, in training.
</P>
<P>
In the women's singles, Lidya Djaelawidjaja, who ousted top-
seeded Camilla Martin of Denmark in the quarter-finals, managed to
beat Ellen Angelinawati 11-8, 9-11, 11-2 in the final. Lidya said
she was happy to win the first title in the Indonesia Open.
</P>
<P>
Defending men's doubles Ricky Subagja and Rexy Mainaky took the
title after beating top-seeded Candra Wijaya/Tony Gunawan with 15-
12, 15-8.
</P>
<P>
In the mixed doubles final, Indonesian seniors Tri Kusherjanto/
Minarti Timur won their fifth consecutive title in the tournament
by beating their compatriots Bambang Suprianto/Zelin Resiana with
15-3, 15-4.
</P>
<P>
Around 250 players from 13 countries took part in the
tournament in Denpasar, about 1,000 kilometers east of here. The
countries include the Netherlands, Belgium, Denmark, Germany,
Sweden, Malaysia, Thailand, Italy, Singapore, Finland, Japan,
Brunei and host Indonesia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
