<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19990906.0254 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-09-06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Update: Summit of la Francophonie Ends in Moncton </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, September 5 (Xinhua) -- The 8th summit of la
Francophonie ended Sunday morning in Moncton, Canada, with a final
communique and a plan of action stressing the role of young people
for the future.
</P>
<P>
Peace, security, individual rights, education, jobs and new
technology are the common concerns of the young people of the la
Francophonie nations, according to Canadian Prime Minister Jean
Chretien, who chaired the three-day meeting in the capacity of
host.
</P>
<P>
With a traditional topic of youth, which is the theme of the
Moncton summit, the meeting was for the first time distracted by
tense dispute over the human rights issue.
</P>
<P>
Police arrested a delegate from the Democratic Republic of
Congo and two other Congolese Saturday when they were approaching
for a fight over the issue outside the summit building. The
delegate was later released.
</P>
<P>
Of the 52-member summit of la Francophonie, 32 African nations
were named as "human rights abusers" by some media and
organizations, giving rise to open wrangling about their
membership.
</P>
<P>
Chretien and French President Jacques Chirac told the final
press conference Sunday that they were opposed to sanctions or
expulsion of member states from the group of 49 nations.
</P>
<P>
The biannual summit of la Francophonie was first held in 1986,
when 41 governments were represented. Membership has since
expanded to 52 governments, including the participating
governments of New Brunswick and Quebec of Canada. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
